# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: akrotiri-and-dhekelia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] 112 is a part of the GSM standard and all GSM-compatible telephone handsets are able to dial 112 even when locked or, in some countries, with no SIM card present.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] It is also the common emergency number in nearly all member states of the European Union as well as several other countries of Europe and the world.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] 112 is often available alongside other numbers historically used in the given country to access emergency services.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] In some countries, calls to 112 are not connected directly but forwarded by the GSM network to local emergency numbers (e.g., 911 in North America, 999 in the United Kingdom and Hong Kong, and 000 in Australia).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] 112 was first standardised as the pan-European number for emergency services following the adoption of recommendation by the European Conference of Postal and Telecommunications Administrations (CEPT) in 1976 and has since been enshrined a CEPT Decision ECC/DEC/(17)05.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] The European Emergency Number Association, founded in 1999, an organization of emergency services representatives and others, has campaigned for an efficient 112 service all over Europe on behalf of European citizens.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] EENA continues to promote awareness of 112 as a core element of its mission.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] After adoption in continental Western Europe, other countries began to use the 112 number for emergencies.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] In many countries, emergency numbers previously used also continue to be available; e.g.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] 061 and 112 in Spain, 999 and 112 both function in Ireland and the UK.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] In the United States, only some carriers, including AT&T will map the number 112 to its emergency number 911.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] The number is also adopted by candidates for EU accession and members of the EEA agreement.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] The International Telecommunication Union recommends that member states selecting a primary or secondary emergency number choose either 911, 112 or both.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] 112 is one of two numbers (the other being the region's own emergency number) that can be dialed on most GSM phones even if the phone is locked.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] 112 is managed and financed in the European Union by each member state, which also decide on the organization of the emergency call centres.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] Adopted in July 1991, the Council Decision 91/396/EC introduced ‘112’ as the European emergency number.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] The Open Network Provision Directive in 1998, the Universal Service Directives in 2002 and 2009 and finally the European Electronic Communications Code in 2018 further specified how 112 should work in the European Union.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] By the European Electronic Communications Code, everyone in the European Union should be able to contact the emergency services by using the European emergency number ‘112’ free of charge wherever they are in the European Union.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] Member States are also required to make sure that access to the emergency services for people with disabilities is equivalent to that enjoyed by other end-users.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] Reverse 1-1-2 is a public safety communications technology used by public safety organizations throughout the world to communicate with groups of people in a defined geographic area.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] Reverse 112 allows authorities to rapidly warn those in danger, directly through their mobile phones.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] This objective can be achieved with either the Cell Broadcast or the Location-based SMS technology.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] The European Parliament, the Council of the European Union and the European Commission signed a tripartite convention in 2009 in order to introduce an annual European 112 Day.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] It is supposed to raise awareness for the Europe-wide availability and the advantages of the European emergency call 112.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] They chose 11 February since the date includes the telephone number (11/2).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] A wide variety of events take place around Europe every year to celebrate European 112 Day.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] Getting 112 to work across the EU is a complex task.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] It requires in particular coordination between civil protection administrations (the emergency authorities who handle the call) and electronic communications administrations (who have to make sure that a 112 call reaches the emergency operator).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] That is why the European Commission decided to act at European level and set up the Expert Group on Emergency Access (EGEA) at the end of 2005.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] The group met for the last time in May 2013.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/112-emergency-telephone-number] In 2020, the European Commission set up the Expert Group on Emergency Communications (EG112) with the task to assist the European Commission in the preparation of new legislations on the matter and exchange views on how emergency communications are handled within the European Union.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The largest enlargement of the European Union (EU), in terms of number of states and population, took place on 1 May 2004.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The simultaneous accessions concerned the following countries (sometimes referred to as the "A10" countries): Cyprus, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Malta, Poland, Slovakia, and Slovenia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Seven of these were part of the former Eastern Bloc (of which three were from the former Soviet Union and four were and still are member states of the Central European alliance Visegrád Group).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Part of the same wave of enlargement was the accession of Bulgaria and Romania in 2007, who were unable to join in 2004, but, according to the European Commission, constitute part of the fifth enlargement.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] With the end of World War II in May 1945, Europe found itself divided between a capitalist Western Bloc and a communist Eastern Bloc, as well as Third World neutral countries.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The European Economic Community (EEC) was created in 1957 between six countries within the Western Bloc and later expanded to twelve countries across Europe.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] European communist countries had a looser economic grouping with the USSR known as Comecon.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] To the south there was a non-aligned communist federated country – Yugoslavia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Between 1989 and 1991, the Cold War between the two superpowers was coming to an end, with the USSR's influence over communist Europe collapsing.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] As the communist states began their transition to free market democracies, aligning to Euro-Atlantic integration, the question of enlargement into the continent was thrust onto the EEC's agenda.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The Phare strategy was launched soon after to adapt more the structure of the Central and Eastern European countries (*Pays d'Europe Centrale et Orientale (PECO)*) to the European Economic Community.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] One of the major tools of this strategy was the Regional Quality Assurance Program (*Programme Régional d'Assurance Qualité (PRAQ)*) which started in 1993 to help the PECO States implement the New Approach in their economy.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The Acquis Communautaire contained 3,000 directives and some 100,000 pages in the Official Journal of the European Union to be transposed.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] It demanded a lot of administrative work and immense economic change, and raised major cultural problems – e.g. new legal concepts and language consistency problems.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Malta held a non-binding referendum on 8 March 2003; the narrow Yes vote prompted a snap election on 12 April 2003 fought on the same question and after which the pro-EU Nationalist Party retained its majority and declared a mandate for accession.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Poland held a referendum on 7 and 8 June 2003: voting Yes by a wide margin of about 77.5% with a turnout of around 59%.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The Treaty of Accession 2003 was signed on 16 April 2003, at the Stoa of Attalus in Athens, Greece, between the then-EU members and the ten acceding countries.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The text also amended the main EU treaties, including the Qualified Majority Voting of the Council of the European Union.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The treaty was ratified on time and entered into force on 1 May 2004 amid ceremonies around Europe.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] European leaders met in Dublin for fireworks and a flag-raising ceremony at Áras an Uachtaráin, the Irish presidential residence.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] At the same time, citizens across Ireland enjoyed a nationwide celebration styled as the *Day of Welcomes*.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] President Romano Prodi took part in celebrations on the Italian-Slovenian border at the divided town of Gorizia/Nova Gorica; at the German-Polish border, the EU flag was raised and Ode to Joy was sung; and there was a laser show in Malta, among the various other celebrations.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Limerick, Ireland's third largest city, hosted Slovenia as one of ten cities and towns to individually welcome the ten accession countries.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The then Slovenian Prime Minister Anton Rop was Guest Speaker at a business luncheon hosted by Limerick Chamber.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] 1 EU Association Agreement type: Europe Agreement for the states of the Fifth Enlargement.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] As of May 2011, there are no longer any special restrictions on the free movement of citizens of these new member states.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] With their original accession to the EU, free movement of people between all 25 states would naturally have applied.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] However, due to concerns of mass migration from the new members to the old EU-15, some transitional restrictions were put in place.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Mobility within the EU-15 (plus Cyprus) and within the new states (minus Cyprus) functioned as normal (although the new states had the right to impose restrictions on travel between them).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Between the old and new states, transitional restrictions up to 1 May 2011 could be put in place, and EU workers still had a preferential right over non-EU workers in looking for jobs even if restrictions were placed upon their country.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] No restrictions were placed on Cyprus or Malta.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Despite the fears, migration within the EU concerns less than 2% of the population.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] However, the migration did cause controversy in those countries which saw a noticeable influx, creating the image of a "Polish Plumber" in the EU, caricaturing the cheap manual labour from A8 countries making an imprint on the rest of the EU.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The extent to which E8 immigration generated a lasting public backlash has been debated.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Ten years after the enlargement, a study showed that increases in E8 migrants in Western Europe over the last ten years had been accompanied by a more widespread acknowledgement of the economic benefits of immigration.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Following the 2007 enlargement, most countries placed restrictions on the new states, including the most open in 2004 (Ireland and the United Kingdom) with only Sweden, Finland and the 2004 members (minus Malta and Hungary).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] But by April 2008, these restrictions on the eight members had been dropped by all members except Germany and Austria.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Cyprus, Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Malta, Poland, Slovakia, and Slovenia became members on 1 May 2004, but some areas of cooperation in the European Union will apply to some of the EU member states at a later date.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Since 1974 Cyprus has been divided between the Greek south (the Republic of Cyprus) and the northern areas under Turkish military occupation (the self-proclaimed Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The Republic of Cyprus is recognised as the sole legitimate government by every UN (and EU) member state except Turkey, while the northern occupied area is recognised only by Turkey.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Cyprus began talks to join the EU, which provided impetus to solve the dispute.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] With the agreement of the Annan Plan for Cyprus, it was hoped that the two communities would join the EU together as a single *United Cyprus Republic*.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] However, in a referendum on 24 April 2004 the Greek Cypriots rejected the plan.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Thus, a week later, the Republic of Cyprus joined the EU with political issues unresolved.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Efforts to reunite the island continue as of 2026.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] European Union membership forced the country to suspend its membership in the Non-Aligned Movement with Government of Cyprus insisting on maintaining close ties with the NAM.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Accession of Poland to the European Union took place in May 2004.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Poland had been negotiating with the EU since 1989.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] With the fall of communism in 1989/1990 in Poland, Poland embarked on a series of reforms and changes in foreign policy, intending to join the EU and NATO.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] On 19 September 1989 Poland signed the agreement for trade and trade co-operation with the (then) European Community (EC).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Polish intention to join the EU was expressed by Polish Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki in his speech in the European Parliament in February 1990 and in June 1991 by Polish Minister of Foreign Affairs Krzysztof Skubiszewski in Sejm (Polish Parliament).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] On 19 May 1990 Poland started a procedure to begin negotiations for an association agreement and the negotiations officially began in December 1990.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] About a year later, on 16 December 1991 the European Union Association Agreement was signed by Poland.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The Agreement came into force on 1 February 1994 (its III part on the mutual trade relations came into force earlier on 1 March 1992).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] As a result of diplomatic interventions by the central European states of the Visegrád Group, the European Council decided at its Copenhagen summit in June 1993 that: "the associate member states from Central and Eastern Europe, if they so wish, will become members of the EU.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] That candidate countries have a working market economy, capable of competing effectively on EU markets.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] That candidate countries are capable of accepting all the membership responsibilities, political, economic and monetary.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] At the Luxembourg summit in 1997, the EU accepted the commission's opinion to invite Poland, Czech Republic, Hungary, Slovenia, Estonia and Cyprus to start talks on their accession to the EU.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The negotiation process started on 31 March 1998.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Poland finished the accession negotiations in December 2002.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Then, the Accession Treaty was signed in Athens on 16 April 2003 (Treaty of Accession 2003).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] After the ratification of that Treaty in the 2003 Polish European Union membership referendum, Poland and other 9 countries became the members of EU on 1 May 2004.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Eight of the 10 countries that joined the European Union during the 2004 enlargement are grouped together as the **A8**, sometimes also referred to as the **EU8**.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] They are grouped separately from the other two states that joined Union in 2004, i.e.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Cyprus and Malta, because of their relatively similar ex-Eastern block background, per capita income level, Human Development Index level, and most of all the geographical location in mainland Europe, where the two other states from aforementioned 2004 batch are Mediterranean isles.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] According to BBC News, a reason for grouping the A8 countries was an expectation that they would be the origin for a new wave of increased migration to wealthier European countries.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] They initially proved to be the origin of a new wave of migration, with many citizens moving from these countries to other states within the EU, later giving a way to newer EU members, including Romania, Bulgaria, and increasing migration from southern Europe after the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] After Brexit, the attractiveness of United Kingdom, a market that used to hold the largest share in immigration from A8 states, sharply declined, and the number of EU citizens that left the UK reached new records.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] At 12 years after the enlargement, the EU was still "digesting" the change.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The influx of new members had effectively put an end to the Franco-German engine behind the EU, as its relatively newer members, Poland and Sweden, set the policy agenda, for example Eastern Partnership.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Despite fears of paralysis, the decision-making process had not been hampered by the new membership and if anything the legislative output of the institutions had increased, however justice and home affairs (which operates by unanimity) had suffered.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] In 2009 the Commission saw the enlargement as a success, but thought that until the enlargement was fully accepted by the public future enlargements would be slow in coming.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] In 2012 data published by the Guardian showed that that process is complete.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The internal impact has also been relevant.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The arrival of additional members has put an additional stress on the governance of the Institutions, and increased significantly overheads (for example, through the multiplication of official languages).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Furthermore, there is a division of staff, since the very same day of the enlargement was chosen to enact an in-depth reform of the Staff Regulation, which was intended to bring significant savings in administrative costs.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] As a result, employment conditions (career & retirement prospects) worsened for officials recruited after that date.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Since by definition officials of the "new" Member States were recruited after the enlargement, these new conditions affected all of them (although they also affect nationals of the former 15 Member States who have been recruited after 1 May 2004).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] Before the 2004 enlargement, the EU had twelve treaty languages: Danish, Dutch, English, Finnish, French, German, Greek, Irish, Italian, Portuguese, Spanish and Swedish.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] However, due to the 2004 enlargement, nine new official languages were added: Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovene, Hungarian, Estonian, Latvian, Lithuanian and Maltese.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] A 2021 study in the *Journal of Political Economy* found that the 2004 enlargement had aggregate beneficial economic effects on all groups in both the old and new member states.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] The largest winners were the new member states, in particular unskilled labor in the new member states.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2004-enlargement-of-the-european-union] A 2007 study in the journal *Post-Soviet Affairs* argued that the 2004 enlargement of the EU contributed to the consolidation of democracy in the new member states.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] The **2006–07 UEFA Cup** was the 36th edition of the UEFA Cup, Europe's second-tier club football tournament.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] On 16 May 2007, at Hampden Park, Glasgow, Scotland, Sevilla won their second consecutive UEFA Cup, defeating Espanyol 3–1 on penalties after the match finished 2–2 after extra time.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] Sevilla became the second side to win the competition for two consecutive seasons, following the hiatus of the original record holder Real Madrid achieved in 1985 and 1986.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] Walter Pandiani of Espanyol was the top goals scorer of this UEFA Cup edition with 11 goals.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] A total of 155 teams from 52 UEFA associations competed for the 2006–07 UEFA Cup.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] Associations were allocated places according to their 2005 UEFA league coefficient, which takes into account their performance in European competitions from 2000–01 to 2004–05.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] **Greece (GRE)**: Greek league 6th-placed team PAOK failed to obtain UEFA licence and were replaced by the 7th-placed team, Atromitos.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] **Serbia (SRB)**: Serbia and Montenegro 3rd-placed team Voždovac failed to obtain UEFA licence and were replaced by the 4th-placed team, Hajduk Kula.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] All Serbian club qualified for this season's UEFA competitions though Serbia and Montenegro domestic tournaments, but represented its official successor Serbia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] **Kazakhstan (KAZ)**: Kazakhstan Cup winners Astana failed to obtain UEFA licence and were replaced by Cup runners-up, Kairat.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] The schedule of the competition was as follows (all draws were held at the UEFA headquarters in Nyon, Switzerland, unless stated otherwise).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] The 2006 Serie A scandal resulted in major changes to the clubs that originally qualified in Italy.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] Originally, Roma took the cup winners' place as losing finalists in the 2006 Coppa Italia, as the winners, Internazionale finished in the top four in the league and qualified for the Champions League.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] The other two UEFA Cup places initially went to Lazio and Chievo.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] Lazio, however, as well as the remaining three Champions League qualifiers (Juventus, Milan and Fiorentina), were formally indicted on 22 June on charges relating to the scandal.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] On 14 July, all four of the indicated clubs were penalised by an Italian court and the Italian Football Federation (FIGC).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] Results of the FIGC appeal were announced on 25 July.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] FIFA suspended the Hellenic Football Federation (HFF) from all international competitions on 3 July 2006 because of "political interference in sport" after the Greek government passed a law, giving it control of the sports authorities in Greece.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] After the law was amended to address FIFA's objections, FIFA reinstated the HFF on 12 July.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] The Greek government in response, decided to withdraw all of its funding to the Hellenic Football Federation.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] These matches were held on 13 July and 27 July 2006.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] These matches were held on 8 and 10 August (first leg) and 24 August (second leg) 2006.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] The matches were held on 14 September (first leg) and 28 September 2006 (second leg).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] The top three teams (highlighted in green) of each group qualified for the next round.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] 6. higher number of coefficient points accumulated by the club in question, as well as its association, over the previous five seasons (see paragraph 6.03 of the UEFA regulations).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] The first legs were held on 14 February and 15 February 2007, while the second legs were held on 22 February 2007.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] The first legs were held on 8 March 2007, while the second legs were held on 14 and 15 March 2007.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] The draw for the final stages, included quarter-finals and semi-finals, was held on 16 March 2007 in Glasgow, Scotland.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] The quarter-final matches were played on 5 April and 12 April 2007.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] The semi-final matches were played on 26 April and 3 May 2007.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2006-07-uefa-cup] The final was played on 16 May 2007 at Hampden Park in Glasgow, Scotland.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] A minority proportion of those deposits was from citizens of other countries (many of them from Russia), who preferred Cypriot banks because of their higher interest on bank account deposits, relatively low corporate tax, and easier access to the rest of the European banking sector.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] This resulted in numerous insinuations by US and European media who presented Cyprus as a "tax haven" and suggested that the prospective bailout loans were meant for saving the accounts of Russian depositors.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] No insured deposit of €100,000 or less would be affected, though 47.5% of all bank deposits above €100,000 were seized.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Nearly one-third of Rossiya Bank's cash ($1 billion) was frozen in Cypriot accounts during this crisis.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] The United States' subprime mortgage crisis in 2007–2008 led to a domino effect of negative consequences in the global economy including the European Union.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] The Cypriot economy went into recession in 2009, as the economy shrank by 1.67%, with large falls specifically in the tourism and shipping sectors which caused rising unemployment.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Economic growth between 2010 and 2012 was weak and failed to reach its pre-2009 levels.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Commercial property values declined by approximately 30%.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Non-performing loans rose to a reported 6.1% in 2011, increasing pressure on the banking system.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] With a small population and modest economy, Cyprus had a large offshore banking industry.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Compared to a nominal GDP of €19.5bn ($24bn) the banks had amassed €22 billion of Greek private-sector debt with bank deposits of $120bn, including $60bn from Russian corporations.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Russian oligarch Dmitry Rybolovlev owned a 10% stake in the Bank of Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Cyprus banks first came under severe financial pressure as bad debt ratios rose.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Former Laiki CEO Efthimios Bouloutas admitted that his bank was probably insolvent as early as 2008, even before Cyprus entered the Eurozone.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] The banks were then exposed to a haircut of upwards of 50% in 2011, during the Greek government-debt crisis, leading to fears of a collapse of the Cypriot banks.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] The Cypriot state, unable to raise liquidity from the markets to support its financial sector, requested a bailout from the European Union.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Progress on fiscal and structural reforms was slow.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] After a serious accidental explosion in July 2011 at the Evangelos Florakis Naval Base, the major credit rating agencies downgraded the country's rating in September.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Yields on its long-term bonds rose above 12% and there was concern that the country would be unable to stabilize its banks.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Since January 2012, Cyprus had been relying on a €2.5bn (US$3.236 billion) emergency loan from Russia to cover its budget deficit and refinance maturing debt.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] The loan had an interest rate of 4.5%, with no amortization/repayment until its maturity after 4.5 years, and no penalty if repayment at that point of time was delayed because Cyprus still lacked access to the normal funding markets.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] The received loan was expected to cover all refinancing of maturing government debt and the amount needed for the government's continued budget deficits, until the first quarter of 2013.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] But the received loan did not include any funds for the recapitalization of the Cypriot financial sector.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Looking further ahead, it was generally expected Cyprus would need to apply for an additional bailout loan.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] On March 18, 2013, Cyprus closed all banks due to concerns regarding a likely bank run with a reopening planned for after the scheduled 25 March holiday.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Later that week, the Eurozone revived a previously offered alternative proposal that would require the merging of Laiki and the Bank of Cyprus, the creation of a new bank for all deposits under €100,000, and the creation of a bad bank.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] This plan would imply lower recapitalization costs.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] However, the plan was opposed by president Nicos Anastasiades, who dubbed the plan the "Icelandic solution", due to potential negative effects on the uninsured deposits that would be placed into the bad bank as it could wipe out up to 40% of their value.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Anastasiades refused to agree to potential losses on large deposits, many held by Russians, in contrast to the Europeans who saw them as necessary haircuts.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] German negotiators in fact believed that Laiki and the Bank of Cyprus were already *de facto* insolvent and would need to be bailed-in by part of these large deposits.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Infighting amongst politicians was blamed for the delay, although official sources claimed the legal department of the parliament had not finished drafting the laws.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] In response to the Eurozone plan, which was supported but not 'fully backed' by the European Commission, the Cypriot government proposed an alternative plan that would raise funds by nationalizing the state pension fund and issuing emergency bonds backed by future revenues.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] This plan, however, was rejected by the EU and the IMF.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] On March 21, the ECB announced it would stop emergency Eurosystem low-cost loans to Cypriot banks on the 25th.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Cyprus has seen a number of reactions and responses towards the austerity measures of the bailout plan.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] On 8 November 2012, the Cypriot far-left party Committee for a Radical Left Rally (ERAS) organized the first protest against austerity while the Troika negotiations were still taking place.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Protesters were gathered outside the House of Representatives holding banners and shouting slogans against austerity.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Leaflets with alternative proposals for the economy were distributed in the protest, with proposals including the nationalization of banking, the reduction of the army and the freezing of the army budget, and the increase of the corporate tax.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Members of the New Internationalist Left (NEDA) also participated in the protest.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] On 14 November, NEDA organised an anti-austerity protest outside the Ministry of Finance in Nicosia together with the Alliance Against the Memorandum.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Contract teachers protested outside the House of Representatives on 29 November against austerity measures that would leave 992 of them without a job next year.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] The teachers stormed the building and bypassed the policemen, entering the House chamber.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] The teachers shouted against the banks and poverty.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] A protest by investors was staged on the morning of 11 December outside the House of Representatives, with protesters again storming the House and bypassing the police.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] The protest interrupted the discussions of the House's committee of customs.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] The protesters were asked to leave so that the committee could continue its work, and the protesters left half an hour later.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] A number of protests took place on 12 December.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Members of large families protested outside the House of Representatives against cuts in the benefits given by the state to support large families.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Protesters threw eggs and stones at the main entrance of the House, and a number of protesters tried to enter the building, but were blocked by the police force that arrived to handle the protest.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] It was reported that a woman fainted during the incidents.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] The protesters shouted for the Representatives to come out but no response was given.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] The protesters were joined by members of KISOA (Cypriot Confederation of Organisations of the Disabled, *Κυπριακή Συνομοσπονδία Οργανώσεων Αναπήρων*), who marched from the Ministry of Finance to the House of Representatives to protest against cuts in benefits for people with disabilities.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Later in the day members of public school teachers' trade unions protested outside the Ministry of Finance against the cuts in education spending which could result in the firing of teachers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] The unions staged another protest the next day near the House of Representatives.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Non-resident investors who held deposits prior to 15 March 2013 when the plan to impose losses on savers was first formulated, and who lost at least €3,000,000, would be eligible to apply for Cypriot citizenship.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Cyprus's existing "citizenship by investment" program would be revised to reduce the required amount from €10,000,000 to €3,000,000.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] "These decisions will be deployed in a fast-track manner", President Anastasiades said in an address to Russian business people in the port city of Limassol in 2013.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Other measures were also under consideration, he said, including offering tax incentives for existing or new companies doing business in Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Frozen deposits in Cyprus banks attracted interest from investors and brokers specializing in distressed assets.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] Among firms reported to be dealing in Cyprus bank debt was London-based Exito Partners (formerly Éxito Capital) and Swiss-based Black Eagle Litigation Fund.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2012-2013-cypriot-financial-crisis] A team of 16 Cypriot economists, organized by the citizens group *Eleutheria* ("Freedom"), attributed the crisis to declining competitiveness and increasing public and private debt, exacerbated by the banking crisis.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2024-uefa-european-under-17-championship] A total of 16 teams played in the tournament, with players born on or after 1 January 2007 eligible to participate.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2024-uefa-european-under-17-championship] Germany were the title holders, having beaten France in a penalty shootout in the 2023 final, but were not able to defend their title after failing to qualify for the final tournament.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2024-uefa-european-under-17-championship] In the final, Italy defeated Portugal 3–0 to win their second title, winning their first-ever title at this age level and their just second title after the 1982 triumph.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2024-uefa-european-under-17-championship] For the UEFA European Under-17 Championship final tournaments of 2023 and 2024, Hungary and Cyprus were selected as hosts respectively.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2024-uefa-european-under-17-championship] The following teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2024-uefa-european-under-17-championship] among all eight elite round groups qualified for the final tournament.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2024-uefa-european-under-17-championship] A total of 12 Referees and 12 Assistant Referees were selected by UEFA for the tournament.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2024-uefa-european-under-17-championship] The group winners and runners-up advanced to the quarter-finals.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2024-uefa-european-under-17-championship] In the knockout stage, a penalty shoot-out was used to decide the winner if necessary (no extra time was played).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2024-uefa-european-under-17-championship] There were 94 goals scored in 31 matches, for an average of 3.03 goals per match.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2024-uefa-european-under-17-championship] After the tournament, the Under-17 Team of the Tournament was selected by the UEFA Technical Observer panel.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Since 28 February 2026, the United States and Israel have been at war with Iran and its regional allies.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Hostilities broke out after US–Israeli airstrikes killed Iranian officials and Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] These attacks were launched amidst negotiations to reach a nuclear peace agreement.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran fired back missiles and drones on Israel, US-aligned Arab countries, and US bases; the United Arab Emirates, Saudi Arabia, and Kuwait retaliated.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran blocked the Strait of Hormuz, which disrupted the global economy by causing a fuel crisis.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] In January, the Iran government massacred thousands of civilians in a crackdown on protests.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] In response, President Donald Trump initiated the largest US military buildup in the region since the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The US and Israeli forces launched the war on Iran on February 28.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The US provided many rationales for the war, including preventing Iran from developing a nuclear weapon, regime change, and taking Iran's oil and gas resources.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The attacks damaged military bases, government buildings, schools, hospitals, and heritage sites; it also inflicted civilian casualties.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] In retaliation, Iran launched drones and ballistic missiles at Israel and Arab countries, including Bahrain, Jordan, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, and the Kurdistan Region of Iraq (KRI).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] At the same time, the Hezbollah–Israel conflict escalated into the 2026 Lebanon war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The secretary-general of the United Nations and several countries condemned the US–Israeli strikes; the UN Security Council passed a resolution condemning Iran's retaliatory strikes on Gulf states.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Critics, including legal and international relations experts, criticized the US-Israeli attacks.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The war's economic impact includes the largest ever supply disruption of the global oil market, disruptions to the natural gas, fertilizer, aviation and tourism industries, as well as volatility in financial markets.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] As of 16 June 2026, the cost of the war to the US taxpayers was estimated at US$113.3 billion.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The parties agreed to a two-week ceasefire, beginning on 8 April.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] It came under strain after Israeli attacked Lebanon and Iran refused to re-open the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] After the failure of the Islamabad Talks on April 12-13, the US imposed a naval blockade.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] On 14 June, a memorandum to end the war was announced, and signed on 17 June by Trump at the Palace of Versailles, and by President Masoud Pezeshkian in Tehran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The dual blockade was lifted the next day, but tensions escalated.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] On 28 June, despite multiple clashes, the US and Iran agreed to cease their exchange of attacks.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The war has been referred to by a number of names.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The initial strikes on Iran were codenamed Operation Epic Fury by the United States government, and Operation Roaring Lion by the Israeli government, in line with their codename of Operation Rising Lion for their strikes on Iran during the Twelve-Day War in June 2025.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran codenamed its response Operation True Promise IV, with the "Third Imposed War" being an existing, plain name among Iranian state media, referencing earlier confrontations.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The war has also been referred to by some outlets as the "Third Gulf War" ("Gulf War III"), following the Gulf War from 1990 to 1991, and the Iraq War (2003–2011), which has also been referred to as the "Second Gulf War" ("Gulf War II").
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Due to the war starting during the month of Ramadan, it has been known as the "Ramadan War".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Media outlets that have used this name include Al Jazeera, *India Today*, the Institute of Contemporary Islamic Thought, the state media of Iran, such as the *Tehran Times*, as well as the state media of Houthi-controlled Yemen, such as the Saba News Agency.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] A US- and UK-backed coup d'état in 1953 deposed Iranian prime minister Mohammad Mosaddegh due to his nationalization of the oil industry, strengthening the rule of Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Israel maintained ties with Iran as part of its alliance of the periphery strategy.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Resentment of the Shah's deference to Western interests and his autocratic rule led to the 1979 revolution in which Pahlavi was overthrown and replaced by an Islamic republic.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran severed diplomatic ties with the US and Israel and held the American embassy staff hostage for over a year.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] During the Iran–Iraq War, the US supported Iraq.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] In 1988, a US warship struck an Iranian mine, and the US responded by attacking Iran's navy.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] A few months later, the US mistakenly shot down a civilian Iranian flight.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran started a ballistic missile program to deter Iraqi missile attacks on Iranian cities and to compensate for its lack of a modern air force due to sanctions.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] In 2002, Iran's covert nuclear program was first revealed, and Iran denied seeking a weapon.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] In 2003, Iran's AMAD Project was suspended following Ali Khamenei's fatwa against nuclear weapons.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] In 2005, the US began imposing sanctions targeting Iran's nuclear program, and in 2006 the United Nations Security Council (UNSC) imposed a series of sanctions against Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The US and Israel conducted a campaign of cyberwarfare against Iranian nuclear facilities to disrupt their operations, while Israel assassinated several top Iranian nuclear scientists.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The UNSC concerns about Iran's nuclear program from 2006 led to the multilateral Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPOA) between Iran and the US in 2015.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] In January 2020, President Trump ordered the assassination of Qasem Soleimani, the commander of the Quds Force.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Following the October 7 attacks on Israel and the start of the Gaza war, tensions further escalated with Israel fighting Iran-backed militias across the Middle East, including Hamas, Hezbollah, and the Houthis.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Israeli strikes on the Iranian consulate in Damascus and the assassination of Ismail Haniyeh in 2024 were met with Iranian strikes on Israel in April and October.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] In June 2025, Israel launched the Twelve-Day War by attacking Iranian military and nuclear facilities, provoking Iranian counter-strikes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The US also struck Iranian nuclear facilities during the Twelve-Day War, which ended in a ceasefire.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] In early 2026, Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu lobbied President Donald Trump for a joint military strike on Iran, specifically targeting its leadership.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Following high-level meetings in February, Trump authorized "Operation Epic Fury", with reports citing Israeli intelligence provided by Netanyahu as a decisive factor in the decision.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran has long denied seeking nuclear weapons, saying its enrichment efforts were to generate nuclear power for civilian use.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Despite Iran's compliance with the JCPOA, Trump withdrew the US from the deal in 2018, re-imposed sanctions, and adopted a "maximum pressure" strategy.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The Biden administration kept most of these sanctions, further damaging Iran's economy.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Trump continued the "maximum pressure" approach in his second term.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent labelled the collapse of the Iranian currency in December 2025 as the strategy's "grand culmination".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] At his State of the Union Address in February 2026, Trump claimed Iran had restarted its nuclear program and was developing missiles capable of striking the US.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Trump's claims contradicted his previous claims that Iran's nuclear program was "obliterated" and US intelligence reports that Iran did not pose any threat towards the US, and needed until 2035 to build such missiles to do so.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] On 12 June 2025, the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) found Iran non-compliant with its NPT safeguards agreement for the first time since 2005.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] A few days later, it was reported that Iran had stored highly enriched uranium in an underground facility that was undamaged by US bombings in 2025.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Subsequently, Iran denied the IAEA access to nuclear facilities that had been bombed, but did provide access to all unaffected facilities.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Analysts in the UK and US characterized Iran's strategy as nuclear hedging, developing the technical infrastructure to assemble a weapon on short notice while stopping short of production.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The *Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists* said that Iran was using its enrichment program and uranium stockpiles for leverage in international negotiations, and was willing to dilute or export its higher-level enriched uranium in exchange for sanctions relief and prevention of attacks.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Israel is widely believed to possess nuclear weapons, with a stockpile estimated between 90 and 400 nuclear warheads.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Israel is the only nuclear-armed country that does not officially acknowledge its nuclear weapons capability.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Some scholars have argued that Israel's nuclear weapons have incentivized Iran to develop its own nuclear program, seen as maintaining a balance of nuclear deterrence, or causing a regional nuclear arms race.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Citing security threats, Israel rejects international calls to accede to the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons or to participate in negotiations of a Middle East nuclear weapon free zone.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] This has frustrated both US and UK diplomatic efforts on such a zone.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Scholars also suggest US tacit acceptance of the Israeli nuclear weapons capability is seen as a double standard that undermines its diplomatic credibility in Middle East nonproliferation negotiations.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Tensions between Iran and the United States during negotiations over Iran's nuclear program began to intensify in January 2026 amid Iran's massacres of its civilians in the crackdown of the 2025–2026 anti-government protests.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The US and Iran restarted indirect talks in February, and agreed to meet in Switzerland to finalize the Islamabad Memorandum.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The US began amassing air and naval assets in the region at a level not seen since the outset of the 2003 US-led invasion of Iraq, including a pair of carrier strike groups and hundreds of aircraft at bases in the area.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The US administration accused Iran of building up its nuclear and missile programs to threaten the United States and its interests.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran in turn accused the US of waging "disinformation and misinformation" campaigns against it.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] The Council on American–Islamic Relations accused Trump of manufacturing justifications for war similar to those for the Iraq War while *Qatar Tribune* asserted that the administration was falsely claiming that WMDs were being built in Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Regional actors, including Qatar, cautioned that any escalation could have severe consequences for the Middle East.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p01] Negotiations regarding the Iranian nuclear program were held in February, and on 28 February 2026 the US and Israel conducted military strikes in Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] IRST), Trump, traveling on Air Force One to Texas, authorized Operation Epic Fury.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] US missiles, drones, and Israeli fighter jets began striking Iran the next day, around 9:45 a.m.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The strikes took place during negotiations over Iran's nuclear program, and coincided with the holy month of Ramadan.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The operation was codenamed Operation Roaring Lion by Israel.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Israeli Air Force (IAF) said it struck 500 military targets in Iran in the largest combat sortie in its history.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iranian naval vessels were also targeted.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel said it used over 1,200 bombs in 24 hours.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] US strikes were carried out by planes based around the Middle East and from aircraft carriers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran's supreme leader Ali Khamenei and thousands of Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) personnel, were killed as military bases were attacked.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Strikes hit Tehran's Pasteur Street district, where the presidential palace is, and the National Security Council.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The strikes were coupled with cyberattacks on Iranian infrastructure, media, and phone apps, with messages calling on Iranians to rise up against their government.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The cyberattacks resulted in a near-total internet blackout in Iran, lasting over 60 hours with connectivity dropping to as low as 1% of normal levels, disrupting government communications, state media, and public services.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran restricted internet access, allowing access only to government-approved users until 26 May.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israeli officials said months-long planning preceded the strikes, allowing them to pinpoint targets, attain "tactical surprise", and gain US support.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Attacking during the morning, rather than at night when most of Israel's previous attacks on Iran took place, added to the element of surprise.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel declared a state of emergency, citing expectation of Iranian retaliation, and warned its citizens to remain in protected areas.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel called up 20,000 reservists in addition to the 50,000 on duty.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Israeli Ministry of Health moved its hospital operations underground.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 28 February, Trump released a statement saying the purpose of the strikes was regime change.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump said Iran's "menacing activities" endangered the US and its allies.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] He cited the Iran hostage crisis, support for non-state actors such as Hamas and Hezbollah, and its killings of protesters.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump cited Iran calling "Death to America" and its alleged history of attacking US civilians and soldiers as evidence of Iran's intent against the US.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump and Benjamin Netanyahu warned of the potential threat of nuclear weapons in Iran and called on Iranians to overthrow their government.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israeli defense minister Israel Katz labeled the strikes a "pre-emptive attack" intended to "remove threats to...Israel".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran rejected claims that it intended to attack the US, citing the aggressive posture of the US military as evidence.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran reacted within hours by launching missiles and drones.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran codenamed its response Operation True Promise IV, and state media dubbed the events the Ramadan War.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran struck Israeli targets in Tel Aviv and Haifa as well as countries throughout the Persian Gulf.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Targets included Bahrain's capital Manama, Kuwait International Airport, the United Arab Emirates' capital Abu Dhabi, Riyadh and Eastern Province in Saudi Arabia, and Erbil International Airport and the US Consulate General in Erbil in Iraq.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran reported striking the US bases of Al Udeid Air Base in Qatar, Ali Al Salem Air Base in Kuwait, Al Dhafra Air Base in the UAE, and the US Fifth Fleet headquarters in Bahrain.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 1 or 2 March, Iran struck the radar bases for US THAAD missile defense systems in Jordan, the UAE and Saudi Arabia, destroying at least one.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 1 March, Iran launched more strikes, including missiles and drones on Bahrain, Israel, Jordan, Kuwait, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, and the UAE.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The UK reported "missiles fired in the direction of Cyprus", but "don't believe they were targeted at Cyprus".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] However, the presidents of Cyprus and Northern Cyprus contradicted the claims that any missiles were fired at Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Palau-flagged *Skylight* and Marshall Islands-flagged *MKD VYOM* tankers were targeted off Oman's coast.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Shipping through the Strait of Hormuz slowed to a standstill, with 150 freight ships, including oil tankers, stalled.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] To avert further Iranian strikes, the E3-the UK, France, and Germany- resolved to back "proportionate military defensive measures" against drones and ballistic missiles, signaling the potential for direct involvement.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] British prime minister Keir Starmer said the US could use British bases for "defensive" strikes on Iran and disclosed that Ukrainian and other specialists would aid Gulf efforts to foil Iranian drone strikes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Saudi Crown Prince Salman, with US backing, vowed to employ military force against Iranian incursions, calling Iranian strikes "cowardly" due to Saudi airspace being closed to US and Israeli attackers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump announced that the US had accepted an Iranian proposal to negotiations.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump issued letters to Congress leaders according to the 1973 War Powers Resolution.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 2 March, the US embassy in Kuwait was struck and closed indefinitely.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The US-flagged tanker *Stena Imperative* and the Honduras-flagged tanker *Athe Nova* were struck.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] An advisor to an IRGC commander said he would set fire to any ship coming through the Strait of Hormuz, and added that no oil will leave the area.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Qatar shot down two Iranian Su-24 bombers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Qatari Ministry of Defense announced that Ras Laffan Industrial City, the main Qatari gas facility, and Mesaieed Industrial Area were struck by Iranian drones.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] According to satellite imagery analysis by the Energy Economics and Society Research Institute, Ras Laffan appeared to not have been damaged before the "unprecedented shutdown" which sent fuel prices higher.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The US and Israel attacked the Natanz Nuclear Facility and the Iranian media reported damage to the Khatam-al-Anbia and Gandhi hospitals.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] In a friendly fire incident, the pilot of an F/A-18 of the Kuwait Air Force shot down three US F-15E fighters.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Hezbollah began firing rockets and missiles on Israel in retaliation for the killing of Khamenei.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Hezbollah claimed that the attack was a "defensive act" after more than a year of Israeli attacks despite a 2024 truce.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] It added that it restarted fighting to force Israel to stop its aggression and evacuate from seized Lebanese territories, emphasizing that the move was unrelated to the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Lebanon banned military activities by Hezbollah after the attacks.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] An IDF spokesperson stated the attack was "an official declaration of war by Hezbollah", vowing to "neutralize" the threat.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel struck southern Lebanon, Beirut, and the Beqaa Valley, with the IDF saying it had killed the head of Hezbollah's intelligence Hussein Makled and Adham Adnan al-Othman, the head of Palestinian Islamic Jihad's armed wing, the Al-Quds Brigades.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Royal Air Force station at Akrotiri, Cyprus, was targeted by a drone strike causing damage to a runway.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Another strike on Cyprus led to Greece announcing that it would deploy frigates and F-16s to defend Cyprus from strikes by Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The pro-Iran militant group Iraqi Guardians of Blood Brigades claimed responsibility for attacks on the US Victory Base near Baghdad International Airport and Erbil in the Kurdistan Region of Iraq.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Islamic Resistance in Iraq claimed responsibility for 23 drone strikes on US assets in Erbil.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 3 March, US and Israeli strikes destroyed the Supreme National Security Council (SNSC) headquarters, the Expediency Discernment Council building in Tehran, and what Israeli officials described as an alleged underground nuclear weapons facility called Min Zadai.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The proximity of these strikes to the Bushehr Nuclear Power Plant (about 12 km (7.5 mi) away) prompted the Russian agency Rosatom to suspend construction on new units and evacuate non-essential staff.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] US officials said its forces had severely damaged Iran's naval capabilities, mainly in the Gulf of Oman, where several Iranian warships were destroyed and key bases hit.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Debris from an airstrike damaged Golestan Palace, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, causing UNESCO to issue a statement that damaging UNESCO sites is against international law.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel Katz authorized a ground invasion of Lebanon on 3 March.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] This incursion in southern Lebanon was with forces from the 91st Division with the goal to establish a "security layer" for the Israeli residents of northern settlements against Hezbollah, expecting to destroy their infrastructure in the Israel-Lebanon border.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Lebanese government reported that such Israeli preventive attacks reached Kfarkela and Qouzah, leading the Lebanese army to redeploy from newly established border posts amid escalating Israeli activity in violation of the 2024 Israel–Lebanon ceasefire agreement.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel reported that it killed Daoud Alizadeh, the commander of the Quds Force's Lebanon branch, in Tehran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Western diplomats said Qatar had struck Iran after Iran had attempted to strike Doha's airport and Qatar shot down two Iranian Su-24 bombers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Qatar denied the accusation that it had joined the "campaign targeting Iran".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran warned it would hit all economic hubs in the Middle East, and any defensive European military involvement would be considered an act of war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 4 March, US secretary of state Marco Rubio announced that the US-Israeli attacks on Iran would increase in intensity.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel attacks hit the Basij headquarters.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The IDF announced that an F-35I "Adir" shot down a Russian-made Iranian Yak-130 fighter jet over Tehran, the first time that an F-35 has shot down a crewed fighter jet in air-to-air combat, and the first time the Israeli Air Force shot down an aircraft since 1985.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran launched strikes against the Al Udeid Air Base, and Aramco's Ras Tanura oil refining facility.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The US ordered the evacuation of non-essential workers in Cyprus in anticipation of Iranian strikes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] A ballistic missile launched from Iran was intercepted by NATO air defense systems as it entered Turkish airspace, marking an escalation in the conflict.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Turkey asserted its right to self-defense after the missile landed in Dörtyol, Hatay Province, and NATO secretary general Mark Rutte stated that the alliance was committed to defending Turkey.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] An Iranian frigate, IRIS *Dena*, was sunk in the Indian Ocean by United States Navy submarine USS *Charlotte*, about 40 nautical miles (74 km; 46 mi) south of Galle, Sri Lanka.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The vessel was returning to Iran following its participation in the International Fleet Review 2026 and the multilateral Exercise MILAN at Visakhapatnam, India.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The exercise required ships not to carry ammunition, and the US likely knew the *Dena* was defenseless, since it sent a maritime patrol aircraft to participate.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] It was the first ship sunk by a submarine in active combat since the Falklands War, and the first by an American submarine since World War II.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The government of Azerbaijan said on 5 March that drones from Iran struck Azerbaijan's Nakhchivan exclave damaging an airport and injuring two civilians.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Keir Starmer confirmed UK's bases on Cyprus would be used to defend the airspace of Jordan from Iranian drones, while Italy, the Netherlands and Spain confirmed they would send warships to defend Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Ireland stated it was willing to protect Cyprus and join the European defense coalition mobilized around the island if requested.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The IDF killed Hamas official Wassim Attallah al-Ali in Beddawi, Lebanon.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump said on 6 March that there are "no time limits" for how long the war will continue.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Iranian tanker IRIS *Bushehr* was interned by the Sri Lanka Navy, marking the first instance of a warship being interned in a neutral country since World War II.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 7 March, the US sent a third aircraft carrier, USS *George H.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The British aircraft carrier HMS *Prince of Wales* was placed on advanced readiness to defend British interests in the region.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 7 March, Iranian president Masoud Pezeshkian apologized for strikes on neighboring countries, citing "miscommunication in the ranks.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] He stated those countries would not be targeted unless the US launched attacks from them; however, Iranian attacks continued, highlighting limited control over the Revolutionary Guard chief Ahmad Vahidi.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 8 March, Khamenei's second son, Mojtaba, was designated as Iran's new supreme leader.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israeli airstrikes hit Iranian oil storage facilities, killing four people.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Strikes on fuel depots near Tehran caused a "river of fire" to pour out along the streets, and the city became engulfed in thick black smoke, causing toxic acidic rain to fall in the surrounding area.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Residents were advised by Iranian authorities to stay indoors, wear masks when outside, and conserve food and fuel.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Kuwait reported that two of its officers were killed.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Saudi Civil Defense agency said that a strike on a compound in Al-Kharj killed two people.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] US Central Command announced the death of a seventh US service member from an Iranian attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The UK confirmed its forces had intercepted an Iranian drone headed towards Iraq, and declared its intention to send a Merlin helicopter to the region to detect aerial threats.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] According to the Iranian Red Crescent Society, 65 schools and 32 medical facilities had been targeted, and more than 10,000 civilian sites damaged.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 9 March, NATO confirmed the interception of a second ballistic missile in Turkish airspace.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Turkey deployed six F-16s and air defence systems to Northern Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump claimed that "the war is very complete, pretty much", after speaking with Russian president Putin, and said "we already won the war in many ways." He claimed that the Strait of Hormuz was open and expressed interest in taking it over from Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump went back on some comments during a press conference later that day, supporting Defense Secretary Hegseth in stating that the war was just the "beginning of building a new country" and it would end "soon".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Following Syrian president Ahmed al-Sharaa's support for the Lebanon's objective to disarm Hezbollah, the group targeted the city of Inkhil in Syria.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] About a dozen B-1B bombers arrived at bases in Europe.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] GPS jamming of uncertain origin disrupted navigation of ships near the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The United States Department of State designated the Muslim Brotherhood branch in Sudan as a terrorist organization.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 10 March, an IRGC commander stated that Iran was only firing missiles with payloads of 1,000 kg or more.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] AFP reported that Iran's attacks were the "most intense and heaviest" since the start of the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] This showed a shift in tactics from saturating air defences to high-impact penetration strikes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] American general Dan Caine acknowledged that Iran was fighting back, but not harder than the US expected.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Following the Syrian presidency's support for the disarmament of Hezbollah and a campaign of mobilization by the Syrian army on the Lebanese border, shells from Lebanon landed in Serghaya, 20 km (12 mi) from Damascus where the Syrian Armed Forces forces presided.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel issued an urgent evacuation notice to southern suburbs of Beirut.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Defense analyst AJ Jaff reported that Iran's ballistic missile launch rate fell 92% from day one of the war (480 to 40) and the drone launch rate fell 92% (720 to 60).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 11 March 14 US bombers were deployed to RAF Fairford in the UK, where bombs were being prepared for loading.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] This followed US war secretary Hegseth's statement that it was the "most intense day of strikes inside Iran".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel reportedly struck the Parchin military complex.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] A branch of Bank Sepah in Tehran was hit by a strike, prompting the IRGC to warn that they could retaliate by striking US or Israeli banks in the region.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran hit Stryker, a US-based medical supply company with a cyberattack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 12 March, UNICEF reported that 300 children had been killed, thousands injured, hundreds of thousands displaced, and millions unable to attend schools due to the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iranian deputy intelligence minister Akbar Ghaffari was killed in an airstrike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] An Iranian attack set two tankers on fire off the Iraqi coast, killing one person.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The historical Safavid-era building of Rashk-e Jenan, was destroyed by US-Israeli strikes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Other buildings damaged included the Chehel Sotoun pavilion, Rakib Khaneh Mansion, Timurid Hall, Ashraf Hall and the Ali Qapu palace.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Many affected buildings and monuments were legally protected by the Blue Shield International, which called damaging them a war crime.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] French soldiers were injured in a drone strike at a base in Iraqi Kurdistan.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] French president Emmanuel Macron announced on 13 March that a soldier was killed in the attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 13 March, to help deal with the economic costs of the war, the US temporarily lifted restrictions on the sale of Russian oil.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran announced a coordinated offensive by its navy, army, and Hezbollah against Israel and US bases.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel reported that 58 people have been hospitalized due to injuries following a missile strike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Kuwait authorities stated that defense equipment and the country's main airport were attacked, and power lines gone out of service.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Missiles entered Turkish air space and were intercepted, with explosions heard near Adana.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel struck IRGC checkpoints after receiving tip-offs by on the ground informants.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Reuters reported Israel had struck positions of the Basij used to suppress Iranian protests.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] As of the third week, analysts found little evidence of significant defections in the Iranian military, which have been considered a necessary condition for regime change.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The US conducted an attack on Kharg Island, a key oil export hub home to 90 percent of Iran's oil exports.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Over 90 military sites were targeted while the oil infrastructure was not targeted "for reasons of decency", according to Trump.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 14 March, Kata'ib Hezbollah security commander Abu Ali al-Askari was killed in an airstrike in Baghdad.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Royal Tulip Al Rasheed Hotel in Baghdad's Green Zone was hit by a drone whilst hosting an EU and Saudi Arabian delegation.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The attack was not claimed by anyone; however, due to the proximity of a similar attack 48 hours earlier on the US embassy in Baghdad, there were suspicions it was an Iranian attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 16 March, China and US-aligned NATO nations in Europe rejected Trump's call to provide military support to reopen the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump rebuked his NATO allies, calling their decision a "very foolish mistake".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On the same day, White House Press Secretary Karoline Leavitt stated that the Trump administration will not rule out a military draft for the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] While doing so, she clarified that a draft is not "part of the current plan," but that the president is open to any suggestions.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 17 March, Trump made a statement on Truth Social renouncing NATO's assistance, and unexpectedly, US allies in the Indo-Pacific, namely Japan, South Korea, and Australia, for refusing to join US-led attacks on Iran during the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump declared that the United States "[does] not need the help of anyone" regarding the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] In the morning of 17 March, senior Iranian officials, including Ali Larijani and Basij chief Gholamreza Soleimani were targeted by Israeli airstrikes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Both their deaths were later confirmed by Iranian state media.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] In response, Iran launched a missile barrage that killed two Israeli civilians in Ramat Gan.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The same day, Israel launched a ground invasion of southern Lebanon.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 18 March, Israel struck the South Pars natural gas field in the Persian Gulf and its neighboring refineries in Iran with US coordination.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] In retaliation, Iran attacked the world's largest LNG production facility in Qatar.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump claimed he was unaware of the South Pars attack, promised that there would be no more Israeli attacks on Iranian oil infrastructure, and threatened Iran not to continue attacking Qatari energy infrastructure.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel said it had killed Iranian intelligence minister Esmaeil Khatib in an overnight airstrike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] A hair salon in Beit Awwa was struck by a projectile, killing four women, with Israeli authorities stating that it was most likely cluster munitions and Palestinian authorities saying it was an errant Israeli interceptor.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 19 March, a US F-35 made an emergency landing after a suspected hit by Iranian forces.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] A BAZAN Group refinery in Haifa was hit during a broader Iranian missile attack on the area as a retaliation for Israeli attacks on South Pars gas facilities.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Netanyahu insisted that "You can't make a revolution from the air" and that "there must be a ground component—I won't share with you all the options", implying that there was a potential for limited assault operations involving soldiers on the ground in Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The US began an aerial campaign against Iranian vessels and drones in the Strait of Hormuz in an effort to reopen it to international shipping.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Admiral Brad Cooper said that the US military had so far struck more than 8,000 Iranian military targets, including 130 vessels.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 21 March, the US conducted strikes on the Natanz Nuclear Facility using bunker buster bombs to target the site.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Russia condemned the strikes on Natanz as a "blatant violation of international law," while the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) urged military restraint "to avoid any risk of a nuclear accident".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] In response, Iran struck the southern Israeli town of Dimona, injuring at least 78 people.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran said that it targeted the Shimon Peres Negev Nuclear Research Center.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Citing unnamed US officials, CNN and *The Wall Street Journal* reported that Iran unsuccessfully attempted to strike the joint US–UK military base at Diego Garcia on the Chagos Islands in the British Indian Ocean Territory.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The report said one of the missiles broke apart mid-flight, while another was intercepted by a SM-3 air defence missile launched by a US warship.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel said that Iran used a two-stage intercontinental ballistic missile to target the island.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran denied launching missiles towards Diego Garcia, saying that it was an Israeli false flag attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] In response the UK Foreign Secretary confirmed and denounced the Iranian attack on their end, and additionally expanded permission for the United States to bomb certain targets using their bases.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] No evidence has been presented that the alleged Iranian missiles neared Diego Garcia or that one was intercepted.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Houthi movement in Yemen warned that it would respond to any escalation against Iran, including efforts to reopen the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] It specifically warned the two Arab countries offering to join the Strait of Hormuz campaign—Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates—that they "will be the first to lose in this battle".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Houthis further threatened to join the war in the event that US allies joined the attack on Iran or if the US and Israel used the Red Sea to carry out operations.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Lebanon's government expelled the Iranian ambassador.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump issued an ultimatum to Iran, threatening to strike its power plants unless it opened the Strait of Hormuz within 48 hours.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran doubled down, threatening to "completely" close the Strait of Hormuz and strike vital infrastructure across the region such as energy and desalination facilities critical for drinking water.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran denied the talks ever took place or were taking place and called the president "deceitful".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran rejected the 15-point peace plan presented by the US.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran asserted that Lebanon must be included as part of a ceasefire deal, thereby making a ceasefire conditional on an end to the 2026 Lebanon war against Hezbollah.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 24 March, Israel or its allies shot down an Iranian missile crossing above Lebanon at high altitude, according to the Lebanese army, which also confirmed that the missile was not targeting Lebanon.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] This was the first time during the current conflict when a shootdown of an Iranian missile took place over Lebanese territory.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] A US strike on the Habbaniya military base—which hosts units from the Popular Mobilization Forces—in Al Anbar Governorate killed seven members of the Iraqi Armed Forces and injured 13 others.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] In response, Iraqi prime minister Mohammed Shia' al-Sudani summoned the US embassy's chargé d'affaires in Baghdad.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iranian state media threatened that Iran could seize Bahraini and Emirati territory if the US "makes any mistakes", while signaling its readiness to open a new front in Yemen by closing the Bab al-Mandab Strait together with the Houthis.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel said it killed Iran's top naval commander, Alireza Tangsiri, purportedly as part of an effort to reopen the Strait of Hormuz, which Katz said Tangsiri was "directly responsible" for the closure of.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 27 March, a day after Trump and Hegseth announced the "neutralization" of Iran's military, an Iranian missile and drone strike on Prince Sultan Air Base damaged several US refueling aircraft and injured at least 15 US soldiers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] An E-3 Sentry was also damaged by the strike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Military analyst Cedric Leighton described the attack as a "a serious blow to [US] surveillance capabilities".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The same day, Iran blocked two Chinese ships from entering the strait and sought to formalize fees for ships passing through it.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Despite pushes for talks, Israeli defense minister Israel Katz publicly vowed to "intensify and expand" Israeli attacks in Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The same day, the Shahid Khondab Heavy Water Complex in Arak—which has in the past been used to test uranium enrichment—and the Ardakan yellowcake production plant in Yazd Province were confirmed to have been damaged in Israeli airstrikes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Houthis joined the war on 28 March launching a ballistic missile towards Israel.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Houthis said that they had launched ballistic missiles targeting "sensitive" military sites in Israel, and vowed to continue the attacks "until the aggression on all resistance fronts stops".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The missile was intercepted and no casualties were reported.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The Houthis subsequently launched a second missile at Eilat.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] In response, the internationally recognized Yemeni government condemned Iran's "frequent attempts to drag Yemen" into conflict "through its terrorist militias".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On the same day, 2,500 US marines from the 31st Marine Expeditionary Unit arrived in the Middle East, expected to be part of US efforts to open the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] US Central Command (CENTCOM) stated that it had struck over 11,000 targets in Iran since the beginning of the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 28 March, joint US–Israeli airstrikes severely damaged several residential and civilian facilities, including the Iran University of Science and Technology.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] In response, Iran threatened to attack Israeli and American colleges across the Middle East.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Airstrikes also struck a 10,000-cubic-meter water reservoir in Haftkel, in Khuzestan province.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] An Iranian missile struck a chemical plant in the Ne'ot Hovav industrial zone, injuring one person and causing fears of a hazardous leak.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] A convoy of the Iraqi Popular Mobilization Forces was seen entering Khorramshahr in southwestern Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Eleven-year-old child soldier Alireza Jafari died following an Israeli drone strike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 29 March, Trump stated that he would prefer to "take the oil in Iran".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] He proposed taking Iran's oil export center, Kharg Island, claiming that the United States could capture the territory "very easily", and implying that the US could occupy it for some time.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On 30 March, Trump said that if a deal were not reached soon and the Strait of Hormuz reopened, the US would strike all of Iran's power plants, oil wells, Kharg Island, and possibly all its desalinization plants, although the feasibility and strategic value of some of Trump's threats were contested.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] On the same day Turkey and NATO intercepted the fourth missile directed towards Turkish territory.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran denied firing a missile at Turkey, claiming that it was a false flag attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The US began flying B-52 bombers over Iranian territory for the first time, indicating its confidence of air supremacy over Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] The US used bombers to target an ammunition depot and air base in Isfahan, causing large explosions.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] U.S-allied Gulf states such as Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Kuwait, and Bahrain reportedly pushed Trump to continue the war until there are significant changes in Iran's leadership.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p02] American journalist Shelly Kittleson was kidnapped in Baghdad by Kata'ib Hezbollah—the strongest faction within the PMF—who demanded that the Iraqi government release several detained members of the group.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 1 April, Mehr News Agency, a semi-official Iranian government news outlet, reported that policy expert and former foreign minister Kamal Kharazi was seriously injured and his wife was killed in an airstrike which hit his home.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian officials described the attack as an attempt to derail diplomacy, noting that Kharazi was overseeing a possible meeting between Iranian officials and US vice president JD Vance.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Airstrikes on the strategically important Hengam Island in the Strait of Hormuz caused seven injuries.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Netanyahu asserted that the US–Israeli strikes have eliminated Iran's ability to produce nuclear weapons and ballistic missiles, thereby removing "two existential threats" to Israel.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 2 April, two US strikes on the B1 bridge between Tehran and Karaj, which was described as the highest bridge in the Middle East, reportedly killed eight people and wounded 95 others, causing it to collapse.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Experts assessed the attack as a possible war crime; it was celebrated by Trump.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] At the time of the attack, many Iranian families had been gathered in the parks below the bridge to celebrate Sizdah Be-dar.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran revealed major damage to the century-old medical center Pasteur Institute of Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] US defense secretary Hegseth boasted of "death and destruction from the sky all day long".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The IDF also announced that one of its strikes in the Kermanshah area of Iran killed Iranian ballistics missile chief Makram Atimi and several battalion commanders from Atimi's central Iranian ballistic missile unit.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] An Iranian ballistic missile strike damaged an Israeli drone factory in Petah Tikva.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Iran's army chief, Amir Hatami, stated that if US forces invade the country, "not a single person" among the invaders will survive.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 3 April, Iranian forces shot down a US Air Force F-15E Strike Eagle fighter jet over the country, with the wreckage falling in the Kohgiluyeh and Boyer-Ahmad province of Iran, prompting a search and rescue mission by US helicopters.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The pilot was rescued that same day, but the WSO remained missing and was rescued alive 48 hours later.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] A US A-10 "Warthog" aircraft was downed and its single crew member ejected near the Strait of Hormuz and was rescued.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran released a video showing shooting down the aircraft using surface-to-air missile.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Tehran's Shahid Beheshti University was hit by airstrikes, making the total number of universities hit to more than 30, according to the Iranian Minister of Science.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 4 April, explosions were reported at an auxiliary building of the Bushehr Nuclear Power Plant as well as the Mahshahr Special Petrochemical Zone in Mahshahr, Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The airstrikes in Mahshahr killed at least five and injured 170 others.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] An Iranian missile strike hit in the vicinity of the IDF's HaKirya headquarters in Tel Aviv.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 6 April, the IRGC announced that the head of the IRGC's intelligence organisation, Major General Majid Khademi, had been killed in a joint US-Israeli airstrike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Their statement claimed that Khademi had "played a major role in Iran's intelligence and security apparatus over nearly five decades".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel said that Yazdan Mir, a high-ranking commander of the IRGC Quds Force, had also been killed in the attacks.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, before Trump's deadline for targeting Iranian infrastructure, Israel carried out strikes on the South Pars Petrochemical facility in Asaluyeh, Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The Israeli Air Force said that "85% of Iran's petrochemical exports" had been taken offline by now.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] At least 34 people, including six children, were killed in US-Israeli airstrikes across Iran, including against Sharif University of Technology and residential areas.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian vice president and reformist politician Mohammad Reza Aref, who is also an alumnus of the university, described the alleged use of a bunker-buster bomb as a "symbol of Trump's madness and ignorance".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 7 April, The Rafi'-Nia synagogue in central Tehran was destroyed in an airstrike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel said that the building was destroyed due to collateral damage and that it was never meant to be the direct target of the airstrike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, US forces began strikes on Kharg Island.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] In response, Iran said its restraint in targeting oil infrastructure in the region would no longer apply.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump posted to Truth Social that "a whole civilization will die tonight, never to be brought back again", causing international concern that Trump would use nuclear weapons.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The Secretary General of Amnesty International said that Trump's statement "may constitute a threat to commit genocide".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Multiple right-wing commentators and many Democrats condemned the post, and some called for him to be removed through the 25th Amendment.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The White House denied considering using nuclear weapons.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The White House later said that "only the president knows" what he would do on Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 7 April Trump announced that the US and Iran had reached an agreement based on the 10-point proposal mediated by Pakistani prime minister Shehbaz Sharif and Field Marshal Asim Munir.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The US, Israel, and Iran agreed to a two-week ceasefire, under which Iran would re-open the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] After the announcement, Iran's Lavan Island oil refinery and Sirri Island crude export facilities were struck; no party claimed responsibility.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] In response, Iran continued missile and drone strikes on Gulf Arab states.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The refinery attack was later revealed to have been done secretly by the UAE.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel and the US asserted that the ceasefire did not include Lebanon, contradicting the Pakistani mediators and Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Hezbollah said it had halted attacks on Israel and on Israeli soldiers in Lebanon.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Despite the ceasefire, Israel launched "Operation Eternal Darkness", which included targeting all Hezbollah's command and control centers in southern Lebanon, Beirut and the Beqaa Valley.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] These were the largest attacks since the start of the war, killing at least 357 people and injuring more than 1,200.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] In Beirut alone, 92 people were killed and at least 740 injured.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] In response, Iran threatened to attack Israel "if the aggressions against dear Lebanon are not brought to an immediate end", Iran paused Hormuz traffic over Israeli attacks in Lebanon.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Hezbollah claimed responsibility for launching rockets towards northern Israel as a response to "ceasefire violations".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 11 April, Trump said that American forces had started "clearing" the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran claimed that an American ship on its way to the strait turned back after being warned.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] *The Wall Street Journal* reported US Navy destroyers entered the strait for the first time since the war began.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The Iranian government reportedly threatened to attack the ships, accusing the US of a ceasefire violation.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] US Central Command said the ships are taking part in minesweeping.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump declared that the US Navy would begin its blockade of "all Ships trying to enter, or leave, the Strait of Hormuz" from 13 April.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] He said the US Navy would stop any ships that paid tolls to Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] However, United States Central Command clarified that the blockade would only be enforced on ships travelling to or from Iranian ports.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The IRGC Navy said any military vessel approaching the strait would be considered a ceasefire violation and meet a "severe response." Trump threatened to strike fast-attack ships of the IRGC Navy, similar to US strikes on drug traffickers during Operation Southern Spear.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran had 13 days of oil storage capacity, forcing it to shut down its oil fields and potentially damaging them.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] An analyst estimated loss of import and export capacity would be US$435 million per day.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 14 April, four Iranian-linked ships traveled through the strait, despite the US blockade.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] They later stopped or turned around, after presumed interception by the US Navy.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Tankers leaving Chabahar Port were contacted by a US destroyer, while Boeing P-8 Poseidon aircraft were also used to intercept tankers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 16 April, Trump announced that Israel and Lebanon agreed to a ten-day truce.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran announced that passage of commercial vessels through the strait would be allowed during the truce.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Despite this, Trump said that the blockade would continue, so Iran announced it would reimpose restrictions on the strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The US stated that its blockade had intercepted 23 ships.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 19 April, Trump sent negotiators to Pakistan.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] He threatened that Iran would be "blown up" if the negotiations failed, saying the US will target power plants and bridges.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The US Navy seized an Iranian cargo ship on 19 April, saying it was attempting to evade the blockade.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran called this a breach of the ceasefire due to end on 22 April.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran retaliated by launching drones at US ships, though no damage was reported.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 21 April, the Pentagon said US soldiers boarded a tanker in the Indo-Pacific region to disrupt ships providing support to Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump said the US military intercepted a "gift from China" to Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] China stated that it "opposes any malicious association".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Hours before the ceasefire was due to end, Trump extended it, saying he did so at Pakistan's request, to allow time for an Iranian proposal.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Hours afterwards, the IRGC announced that it had seized two container ships and fired on one.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] This was in response to the US seizing an Iranian ship three days earlier.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 22–23 April, three Iranian oil tankers were intercepted by the US.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Despite Iran's seizure of two cargo ships, Trump claimed total control over the strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] *The Guardian* described the situation as a "dual blockade", saying that while the US Navy could blockade Iranian ports, it had been unable to stop Iran's blockade and open the strait to allies.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel and Lebanon agreed a three-week extension of their ceasefire.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 24 April, Iran said it seized a ship suspected of collaborating with the Americans after the ship ignored warnings.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 25 April, Trump canceled US negotiators' trip to Pakistan.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 3 May, Trump said the US would help free up ships in the strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 4 May, the UAE and Oman said they had intercepted Iranian missiles, and drones.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian state media said Iran's navy fired missiles and hit an American frigate.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM denied the missiles struck the ship.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] US Forces destroyed six small Iranian boats after they allegedly attempted to interfere with the transit of two US flagged commercial ships and two destroyers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The UAE said an Iranian drone strike on an oil processing plant in Fujairah caused a fire, injuring Indian citizens.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 6 May, Trump announced a pause in the US military's "Project Freedom" to reopen the strait for "a short period", citing "great progress" toward an agreement with Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] *NBC News* reported that Trump's sudden announcement angered Saudi leaders who supported the diplomatic process in Pakistan.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Saudi Arabia responded by not allowing the US military to fly aircraft from Prince Sultan Air Base or fly through Saudi airspace, which forced the pause in operations.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 7 May, the US said it had struck Iranian military sites in Bandar Abbas and Qeshm Island in response to a missile, drone, and boat attack on US destroyers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran accused the US of violating the truce by targeting an Iranian oil tanker and another vessel.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] It said the US strikes hit civilian areas in Qeshm Island, and coastal areas in Bandar Khamir and Sirik.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran said it targeted American military vessels in response.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The UAE claimed that its air defense systems shot down Iranian ballistic missiles.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The US said that it carried out strikes on two oil tankers allegedly attempting to reach Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian officials said that six people went missing and others were injured in US attacks, which hit "Iranian fishing and cargo vessels".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 9 May, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that Israel constructed a military base in a desert region of Iraq to support its air campaign, and launched airstrikes against Iraqi soldiers who almost found the base, killing a soldier.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 17 May, Iraqi officials confirmed another base in Iraq was held by Israel.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 10 May, UAE and Kuwait reported drone incursions that were neutralized, and a fire on a vessel off Qatar following a drone attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The next day, the US dispatched the submarine USS Alaska (SSBN-732) to Gibraltar to put pressure on Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] *The Wall Street Journal* reported that the UAE has been discreetly striking Iran, including a strike on an oil refinery on Lavan Island in April, and that the UAE was coordinating with Israel.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] US Ambassador to Israel Mike Huckabee announced that Israel had sent Iron Dome batteries, and personnel, to the UAE, to deter Iranian assaults.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 12 May, Kuwait accused Iran of attempting to infiltrate Bubiyan Island on 1 May with six troops of the IRGC.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 13 May, Reuters reported that Saudi Arabia had struck Iranian-backed Iraqi militias near the Iraq–Saudi Arabia border around the time of the 7 April US-Iran ceasefire.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Kuwait launched attacks on Iraqi militias from its territory.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Netanyahu's office said he covertly visited the UAE during the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 18 May, Trump said he postponed a "scheduled attack" on Iran for 19 May at the request of Qatar, Saudi Arabia, and the UAE.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 24 May, a US official said that the US and Iran theoretically agreed for Tehran to reopen Hormuz and dispose of highly enriched uranium.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian media reported that Iran intercepted an Israeli Orbiter surveillance drone in its Hormozgan province.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel said it was unaware of any such incident.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 25 May, the US struck targets in Iran, including boats and missile sites.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] According to Iranian sources, prior to the US attacks, the Iranians targeted a ship.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 26 May, Iran said it had downed a US MQ-9 drone and fired towards a fighter jet in its airspace.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] It claimed a US RQ-4 drone and F-35 fighter jet entered its airspace prior to retreating.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 27 May, the US conducted strikes in Iran targeting a military site which officials believed threatened American forces in the strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 28 May, Kuwait downed a ballistic missile launched at its territory.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran said it had targeted the American base in Kuwait responsible for the previous day's attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Debris from the downed Fateh-110 missile fell on Ali Al Salem Air Base, injuring American soldiers and contractors, and destroying a US Reaper drone.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 2 June, US Central Command announced that a Hellfire missile launched from a American jet disabled a tanker heading for Kharg Island, after the vessel "ignored warnings" and did not comply with the US blockade.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 3 June, Iran said it had targeted the US Fifth Fleet headquarters, and an ‌airbase and helicopters, with missiles and drones in response to an American attack on communication towers near Qeshm Island.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] It stated that its navy targeted a ship called *Panaya* using missiles in response to an American attack on an Iranian tanker.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] US Central Command said Iranian missiles fired towards Kuwait fell short ‌or broke apart in flight, while ballistic missiles launched towards regional targets failed.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM said the US military shot down Iranian drones "targeting civilian ships" in regional waters and American forces in Kuwait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] One person was killed during attacks that hit Kuwait airport.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran denied responsibility, claiming the destruction was caused by a malfunction in a US-made Patriot air defence system.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 5 June, CNN reported that Israel had secretly deployed military personnel to Azerbaijan and was operating a facility in Somaliland.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran said it launched warning missiles and drones towards American warships in the Gulf of Oman.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The US rejected the claim, saying doing so would be a violation of the truce.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 6 June, the US announced that it downed Iranian drones fired toward the strait and hit coastal surveillance radar sites in Sirik and Qeshm Island, as a response.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran announced that it had targeted US air bases in Kuwait and a US navy site in Bahrain with ballistic missiles, after the attacks.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM said that of the seven Iranian missiles launched, six were shot down and one failed to reach its target.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 7 June, the US announced that it downed Iranian drones posing a threat to the strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Lebanese ⁠state media said an Israeli strike in the suburbs of Beirut killed two people.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The IDF said that it targeted Hezbollah infrastructure after the group fired towards Israel.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran said that American bases and Israeli assets in the Middle East are legitimate targets due to the American blockade and Israeli strikes on Beirut's suburbs, where Hezbollah members live.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran launched ballistic missiles towards Israel.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran targeted Ramat David Airbase and Israel confirmed that the base was damaged.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel said that it will retaliate "forcefully" to the Iranian violation of the truce.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 8 June, the IDF announced that it struck military sites in Iran, with explosions reported in Tehran, Isfahan, and Tabriz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] This triggered an exchange between the two countries.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Two Iranian soldiers were killed in an Israeli attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran afterwards said it had ceased military actions against Israel.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel stopped strikes at Trump's request.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 9 June, *The New York Times* reported that American crew was rescued after a helicopter went down near the strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM said they were rescued by a US Navy drone boat for the first time.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump said Iranians had shot down the helicopter and pledged to respond.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] A US official said a Shahed one-way attack drone downed the helicopter.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran said it did not deliberately target the helicopter.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM later said that it launched "self-defense" strikes in retaliation.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] One attack damaged water reservoir tanks in Sirik; Iran stated that 20,000 people had lost access to drinking water.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 10 June, Iran said that it launched strikes aimed at the US Fifth Fleet, Ali Al Salem airbase and Muwaffaq Salti Air Base in retaliation to the US attacks.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump promised to strike Iran "very hard", citing inadequate progress in negotiations.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM said US forces disabled an oil tanker in the Gulf of Oman which allegedly violated its blockade.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The Indian External Affairs Ministry condemned the attack in which three Indian crew were killed.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] An Associated Press source said that the tanker received warnings prior to the American strike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump said that the US military secretly facilitated the passage of 100 million barrels of oil across the Strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The US military launched strikes on Iranian targets on 10 June, firing 49 Tomahawk missiles.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] US attacks with precision munition allegedly targeted facilities for providing drinking water near Bemani.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Local authorities claimed 20,000 people were cut off from water supplies.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 11 June, Iran announced the closure of the Strait to oil tankers and commercial ships, threatening to fire upon any vessel attempting to pass and claimed to have struck two ships allegedly trying to transit the strait, claims denied by the US military.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran reported launching attacks on antennas and radar facilities of the Patriot system located at American military bases in Kuwait and Bahrain, as well as on a US command center in Jordan, in retaliation.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Downed Iranian drones landed in populated areas of Bahrain, causing damage to houses.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM executed a strike with Hellfire missiles on a ship in the Gulf of Oman, targeting its engine room while it was transporting Iranian oil.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The ship's crew, all Indian nationals, allegedly did not follow directions from American forces but were rescued.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump announced that the US would take control of Iran's oil and gas markets like it did in Venezuela, stating this would happen soon.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] He threatened to strike Iran "VERY HARD TONIGHT" and seize Kharg Island and other oil infrastructure.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump claimed that the US could take over Iran with small troop deployment, although he did not intend to.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump expressed skepticism about Americans' willingness to support an invasion of Kharg Island.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Key gaps regarding the release of frozen Iranian assets, reopening of the Hormuz, and protocols for managing Iran's nuclear program during a 60-day ceasefire were narrowed in talks between Iranian officials and Qatari mediators, coordinated with the US.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 12 June Pakistan announced that Iran-US peace agreement text was "agreed".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 14 June, Iran said that the draft US deal included Tehran agreeing not to produce or acquire nuclear weapons, and the US agreeing to allow Tehran to dilute its highly enriched uranium stockpile in Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump and Iran announced they had reached an agreement to end the war and reopen the Strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump said he had authorized the lifting of the US blockade.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 15 June, US vice president JD Vance announced that the memorandum was digitally signed by both countries the previous day.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 17 June, Trump stated that if he does not like the agreement with Iran, the US will "go right back to dropping bombs".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Trump and Iranian president Masoud Pezeshkian signed the memorandum of understanding to end the war, with Trump signing it during dinner with French president Emmanuel Macron at the Palace of Versailles after the G7 summit.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 18 June, Pakistan stated that the signing of the memorandum implies Tehran will reopen the Hormuz "instantly" and the American blockade will end "immediately." CENTCOM announced that it had removed the naval blockade.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 19 June, US president Donald Trump announced a renewed ceasefire between Israel and Hezbollah in the 2026 Lebanon war, facilitated by the US, Qatar, and Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Hezbollah announced an attack on Israeli forces trying to capture Ali al-Taher in Nabatieh.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel continued to strike southern Lebanon numerous times.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 20 June, Iran declared that it closed the Strait of Hormuz again due to Israeli strikes in Lebanon, describing them as a violation of its deal with the US.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] This claim was denied by the US military.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Shipping was stalled in the Hormuz following Iran's claimed closure of the strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Some vessels approaching the strait deactivated their automatic identification systems to cross near the Omani shoreline and avoid Iranian military detection.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Trump stated that there will be no tolls for passing through the Hormuz during or after the 60-day interim ceasefire with Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 21 June, Trump issued a threat to invade Iran if they closed the Hormuz, following Iran's claim of its closure.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, the US and Iran agreed to establish a "hotline" to coordinate traffic in the Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 25 June, Iran declared a new Hormuz route laid out by Oman and the International Maritime Organization "unacceptable and dangerous", warning against ships transiting with no approval from it.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, the British military announced that a cargo vessel was damaged by an unknown projectile in the Hormuz 7.5 nautical miles southeast of Omani port of Dahit while travelling via the UN-approved route.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The US accused Iran of carrying out the attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The International Maritime Organization chose to halt its planned evacuation of ships stranded around the Hormuz following the attack, causing oil prices to surge by much to 4%.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 26 June, Iranian state media reported that at least three foreign oil tankers which tried to cross the Hormuz "without authorisation" from Iran had turned back after an Iranian warning.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Iranian state media announced that the United States and Iran had established a communication line in the Hormuz to prevent military confrontations.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, tracking platforms showed that despite Iranian warnings, several ships crossed the Hormuz via Oman.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On that day, Trump accused Iran of violating the truce with US by launching drone attacks on ships in the Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The United States Central Command later announced that in retaliation to the alleged truce violations, the US hit Iranian missile and drone storage facilities, as well as coastal radar stations.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran said that its retaliation to the attack will ⁠be "swift and decisive," prior to deleting the ⁠statement.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 27 June, Iran said it targeted American sites in the Gulf region in response to the attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, the United Kingdom Maritime Trade Operations said that an unidentified projectile struck a tanker in the Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] UKTMO added that the vessel's bridge was damaged, but all crew members were reported safe, and no environmental damage had been detected at the time of the report.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, the Joint Maritime Information Center (JMIC), which is overseen by the US Navy, announced that a route through the Hormuz near Oman has been widened to allow for more naval traffic in both directions, implying that the US is challenging Iran's control over the waterway.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump accused Iran of repeatedly violating the ceasefire memorandum, expressing doubt about their ability to learn from past mistakes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] He warned of a potential point where the US will be forced to militarily "complete the job", stating that if this occurs, the Iranian regime could cease to exist.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 28 June, Iran said it fired ballistic missiles and drones towards the US-operated Ali Al Salem Air Base in Kuwait and the US Fifth Fleet headquarters in Bahrain in retaliation to American attacks against five Iranian coastal sites.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Iranian state television stated that passing through the Hormuz still required coordination with Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, Iran stated that the Hormuz would stay under Iranian control for 30 days and the Islamabad Memorandum grants Tehran control over the waterway.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On that day, a member of the Office of Preservation and Publication of Iran's Supreme Leader's Works told state TV that Iran cancelled participation in technical talks due to recent attacks.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The US and Iran later reportedly agreed to stop exchange of attacks between them and meet that week.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 29 June, Iran denied that technical meetings with Americans are expected for that week, referring to the Iranian week concluding on Friday.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Trump said that a US-Iran meeting would take place the next day in Doha, claiming that Iran requested the meeting.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, Iran reiterated that no negotiations between Iran and Americans are scheduled in the coming days.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran later stated that it opposes vessels crossing outside of Tehran's designated Hormuz channels and will try to prevent them.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 30 June, Qatar confirmed that US envoy Steve Witkoff and Trump's son-in-law ‌Jared Kushner will be in Doha to meet Qatari mediators to discuss negotiations with Iran, but there will not be a high-level meeting between Americans and Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Iran announced that it was unable to export any oil during the US blockade of its ports.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, *The Wall Street Journal* reported, citing official US sources that Trump has discussed with Defence Secretary Pete Hegseth and Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Gen.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Dan Caine the prospect of more strikes against the Iranian regime.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] According to the sources, the discussions focused on whether the US should abandon negotiations and conduct an all-out war against the regime, a move some described as "finishing the job." According to reports, Trump has decided to stay on the diplomatic course for the time being.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump also stated that his deadline for a nuclear deal with Tehran is 18 August, and that he is comfortable if negotiations with Tehran extend past that date.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 1 July, Iranian state television broadcast on-screen alerts about what it falsely claimed as a foreign ship that got struck while rejecting the IRGC navy's orders.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The false claim looked to be intended to bolster Tehran's claim of sovereignty over the Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Marine tracking data revealed that the ship is linked to the Iranian regime.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 2 July, Iran stated that IAEA inspectors will not be permitted entry under any circumstances to the Fordow, Natanz, and Isfahan nuclear sites, which were bombed and damaged by the US, citing a law passed by the Iranian parliament and the Supreme National Security Council.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Iran cautioned oil tankers to take permitted routes through the Hormuz or risk a "forceful response".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 4 July, Trump mentioned the war in a speech commemorating the United States Semiquincentennial, claiming Americans granted the Iranian regime a week off for a funeral.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, the UK and France stated that Oman had committed to work with both countries to ensure safe navigation through its territorial waters in the Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran warned the UK and France against providing military support to defend shipping in the Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, Trump stated that the US could have killed regime officials attending former Iranian Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei's funeral, but doing so would have left no one to negotiate with.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The US and Israel eliminated many Iranian commanders and leaders on the war's first day by causing Iran to believe that strikes were not imminent.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Thus, groups of senior Iranian officials continued gathering in person.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] These gatherings were targeted in initial strikes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] One part of the deception was information about a US F-22 deployment leaked to hide that preparations were more advanced at other bases.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Calls between Trump and Netanyahu before the war were not publicised to diminish the possibility of an Iranian first strike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] IDF spokesperson Brigadier General Effie Defrin stated that months of joint US and Israeli "strategic and operational deception" of satellite imagery led up to the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] This encompassed planes and other facilities.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The night of the initial strike he and IDF Chief of Staff Lieutenant General Eyal Zamir took their official cars home from IDF Headquarters.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] They came back without them so that satellite imagery would show that their base did not appear full nor warplanes appear armed and ready.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Three separate gatherings of Iranian officials were hit within half a minute of each other in the opening strike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 28 February 2026, Ali Khamenei, the supreme leader of Iran, was assassinated in an Israeli air attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 1 March, Iranian state media announced Khamenei's death.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The IRGC-controlled Fars News Agency announced that Khamenei's daughter, son-in-law, grandchild, and daughter-in-law Zahra Haddad-Adel had also been killed.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The Iranian government declared 40 days of mourning.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The initial dead included Iranian defense minister Aziz Nasirzadeh, and four top Ministry of Intelligence officials.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 13 March, IDF estimated that between 3,000 and 4,000 Iranian soldiers and commanders had been killed.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 17 March, Israel assassinated Ali Larijani, secretary of Iran's Supreme National Security Council.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] IRGC commander Mohammad Pakpour and Defence Council secretary Ali Shamkhani were reported dead in late March.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 18 March, the Hengaw Organization for Human Rights estimated that 5,300+ members of the Iranian military had been killed.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 31 March, Iran International reported that at least 4,700 security forces had been killed.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 6 April, the head of IRGC intelligence, Major General Majid Khademi, was assassinated in a joint US-Israeli airstrike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] As of 7 April, Human Rights Activists in Iran (HRANA), a US-based non-governmental organization, reported 3,636 documented war deaths, including 1,701 civilians, 1,221 military personnel, and 714 unclassified.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] According to HRANA, "[i]t is believed that military casualties are significantly higher than the figures reported in [its] reports" as confirmations depend largely on government data.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Its count largely reflects reports of military personnel present in urban areas.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On the first day of the war, the Shajareh Tayyebeh girl's elementary school in Minab was hit by an American attack, according to Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The school was located near the Sayyid al-Shuhada military complex, of which it had once been a part.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] While the number killed was not independently confirmed, Iranian state media reported that more than 175 people, mostly children, were killed while 95 were wounded.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Video showed a Tomahawk missile hitting a building adjacent to the school; preliminary findings from an American military investigation indicated that the strike resulted from outdated targeting data.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] At least 20 civilians, mostly families who gathered after breaking their fast at Ramadan, were killed in Tehran's Niloofar Square on 1 or 2 March, according to Iranian-state media.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 3 March, the Iranian Red Crescent Society said that over 600 civilians had been killed while HRANA reported 1,097 civilian deaths.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 7 March, the Red Crescent reported that over 6,668 civilian "units" had been targeted by US-Israeli strikes, including 5,535 residential units, 1,041 commercial units, 14 medical centers, 65 schools, and 13 centers affiliated with the Red Crescent.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The Middle East Eye, an anti-Israel news outlet, reported that the US used double tap airstrikes, although the US denies this.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] As of 23 March, HRANA estimated that at least 15% of the casualties were under age 18.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] An Israeli airstrike on 9 March in Resalat neighbourhood of Tehran destroyed a Basij-affiliated building as well as three residential buildings, killing 40 to 50.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] According to a BBC analysis, Israel used Mark 82 bombs in the attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] As of 27 March, Iran has reported damage to at least 120 historical sites.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The deadly attack on residential buildings and a sports hall in the town of Lamerd killed 21 including 4 children and injured 100.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The initial attack targeted Leadership House.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 2 March, video footage released by Iran International showed the destroyed IRGC Malek-Ashtar building in Tehran following a joint US-Israel missile strike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 3 March, the complex of Islamic Republic of Iran Broadcasting (IRIB), the state broadcaster's headquarters, was hit in an Israeli air operation.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian state-linked media indicated that Iran's parliament building was targeted.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 3 March, Israeli forces bombed the Assembly of Experts office building in Qom.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] By 5 March, the World Health Organization had identified 13 Iranian health sites hit, as well as one in Lebanon.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The Iranian Foreign Minister said that the US had struck a desalination plant on Qeshm Island, disrupting water supply to 30 villages, but both the US and Israel denied an attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The Russian consulate in Isfahan was damaged.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] After US strikes on 9 June, Iran said that damage to water storage units in Hormozgan province had left 20,000 people without water.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Analysis of satellite images by *the Washington Post* revealed damages to at least 228 structures or pieces of equipment at US bases across the Persian Gulf, far more than the Trump administration has admitted to.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 1 March, six US soldiers were killed amid more than 30 injured in an Iranian drone attack near Camp Arifjan in Port Shuaiba, Kuwait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Those killed were soldiers of the United States Army Reserve assigned to the 103rd Expeditionary Sustainment Command, headquartered in Des Moines, Iowa.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 4 March, US Marine Corps Lance Corporal Kevin Melendez died in Saudi Arabia in a non-hostile incident.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 8 March, CENTCOM reported that a National Guard soldier died during a medical emergency.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Pennington, a soldier of the 1st Space Brigade wounded in an attack against Prince Sultan Air Base in Saudi Arabia on 1 March, died from his injuries on 9 March.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Six American airmen were killed on 12 March when their KC-135 aerial refueling aircraft crashed in western Iraq.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM said that the crash was not the result of hostile action, but had resulted during an incident involving another US aircraft.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] By 13 March, the US military publicly announced that about 140 American servicemen had been injured.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] A 27 March attack on Prince Sultan Air Base damaged "multiple" refueling aircraft and destroyed a Boeing E-3 Sentry, as well as wounding at least 15 US soldiers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Ford*, the largest aircraft carrier in theatre, was damaged by a fire that broke out 12 March.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The US Navy said the fire had injured multiple sailors, started in a laundry area and was not combat-related.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The carrier had been dealing with other mechanical issues, including a malfunctioning sewage treatment system, since before it arrived in the Middle East.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] According to multiple reports on 17–18 March, *Gerald R.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Ford* paused launching airstrikes and sailed toward the Crete Naval Base for repairs.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Many US military bases near Iran were rendered "all but uninhabitable" due to Iranian strikes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Within the war's first two weeks, Iran's attacks caused $800 million in damage to bases.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Affected bases include Al-Sader and Al-Ruwais in the UAE, the naval base in Bahrain, Ali Al-Salem in Kuwait, Al-Udeid in Qatar, and Prince Sultan in Saudi Arabia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] According to unnamed officials, the damage degraded the US's military ability in the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Many US servicemembers relocated to "hotels and office spaces", which raised concerns of the US using civilians as human shields.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] An attack on a hotel in Bahrain injured two Pentagon employees.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Based on numbers given by members of the United States Congress, by May 2026 the United States military had lost 39 aircraft in "Operation Epic Fury".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Magen David Adom reported that Iran's initial attacks had left 89 injured, with three directly wounded and the rest indirectly, most of them civilians.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 28 February, a direct hit in Tel Aviv killed a woman and injured 22 others, one seriously.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 1 March, a strike hit a synagogue and residential buildings in Beit Shemesh, killing nine civilians in a shelter and injuring 49 others.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 9 March, two workers were killed in Yehud, outside of Tel Aviv, after they were struck by submunitions from an Iranian missile equipped with a cluster bomb warhead.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 17 March, a cluster munition from an Iranian warhead hit an apartment building in Ramat Gan and killed two residents.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] A statement from the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps called the missile barrage "revenge for the blood of martyr Dr.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Ali Larijani and his companions", who had been killed the day before in a targeted attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] According to CNN, the use of cluster munitions violates international law.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Jenzen-Jones of Armament Research Services stated that this type of warhead is being used "primarily to sow terror amongst a civilian population".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 4 April, an Iranian missile strike hit in the vicinity of the IDF's Kirya headquarters in Tel Aviv.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Since 2 March 2026, there has been an ongoing war in Lebanon between Israel and the Lebanese Shia militant group Hezbollah, with Israel invading parts of Lebanon.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] It is a resumption of major fighting in the Hezbollah–Israel conflict that began in late 2023, and is part of the wider conflict in the Middle East.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] In Iraq, two members of the Iran-backed Popular Mobilization Forces (PMF) were killed and three injured in a US-Israeli attack on 28 February.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] On 1 and 2 March, the United States and Israel conducted several attacks on Iranian-backed Iraqi militias to degrade their military capabilities.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] In addition to Israel, Iran launched strikes against multiple US-allied Arab countries.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian strikes against Bahrain killed three.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Strikes against Kuwait killed four soldiers and four civilians.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Strikes against Saudi Arabia killed two.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Strikes against the United Arab Emirates killed two soldiers and six civilians.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran also struck Qatar, Azerbaijan, and the Akrotiri and Dhekelia British Overseas Territory on Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p03] The Iranian attacks affected military infrastructure from NATO countries in the region, "including an Italian installation in Iraq and Kuwait, and a French naval facility in the United Arab Emirates".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The death of Ali Khamenei triggered an election for a new supreme leader.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Under the terms of Iran's constitution, the Interim Leadership Council was established on 1 March to exercise the functions of Iran's head of state until a new supreme leader is elected.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Mojtaba Khamenei was elected on 8 March 2026 to replace his father as supreme leader, and the IRGC, as well as Iran's top leaders, including Mohammad Bagher Ghalibaf, Ali Larijani, and Masoud Pezeshkian, pledged their allegiance to him.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] In late March, the NYT described Iran's leadership as paralyzed with severely disrupted decision-making process.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] It also reported that the damage to communications infrastructure caused paranoia and internal power struggles.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] As of 21 May, Khamenei remains in hiding and the de facto ruler is uncertain.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The IRGC is currently under command of the hardliner general Ahmad Vahidi, who is cited as the formulator of Iran's military and negotiation stance.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] According to UN Human Rights Chief Volker Türk, the "reckless" war is disproportionately impacting civilians in the Middle East and beyond.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] 138,000 civilian sites in Iran were damaged during the conflict, with estimated time of reconstruction being 2 to 5 years.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] As the US and Israel executed joint strikes targeting Iranian military and institutional targets, Iran's capital reportedly became a ghost town, as civilians feared going outside or to their daily jobs.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Reports have emerged that prisoners in Evin Prison have been receiving limited bread and water since the onset of the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] After the strikes, schools were ordered closed while banks and government offices remained in operation at reduced capacity.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Local media reported that subway and bus services would remain operational.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Amid the renewed "near total" internet blackout in Iran, NetBlocks reported that internet connectivity in Iran dropped to 4% of ordinary levels.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] While the internet blackout has exceeded 240 hours, making it the second longest ever, the government started handing out "white sim cards", which bypass filters, to government supporters, in order to allow them to promote its messaging.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] As news of Khamenei's death broke, security forces were deployed to prevent an uprising, with footage showing them opening fire on celebrants in the streets and shooting at people chanting behind the windows of their homes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] During the first two weeks of March 2026, over 70,000 Afghan refugees returned to Afghanistan, frequently under forced circumstances, exacerbating the country's severe humanitarian crisis.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Arafat Jamal, the UNHCR Representative in Afghanistan, noted that they faced limited options amid the military confrontations between Afghanistan and Pakistan.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] According to *The Guardian*, the war has overshadowed the executions of political prisoners in Iran, including those involved in the mass protests of January 2026, allowing Iran to continue carrying out death sentences and other severe punishments with little international scrutiny.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] According to several Iran-focused human rights groups, the rate of sentencing and executions by hanging has surged over the past two months amid the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The groups state that in most of these cases, the executed prisoners did not receive due process.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 26 March, it was reported that children as young as 12 years of age may join Iran's war support, leading to concerns of the use of child soldiers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Days later, rights groups stated an 11-year-old was killed while on duty at a Tehran checkpoint.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 29 March, footage showed Iraq's Popular Mobilization Forces deployed in Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] According to *The Wall Street Journal*, Trump had been open to supporting armed militias, particularly Kurds in Iran that have been in armed conflict with Tehran for decades and have historically been a regional ally of the United States.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] However, Trump later said he had ruled out sending the Kurds to Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Multiple historic and cultural sites, including UNESCO World Heritage Sites, were damaged during the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The most affected was Chehel Sotoun and its rich *ayeneh-kari*.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 2 March, a strike on Arg Square damaged nearby Golestan Palace, prompting UNESCO to issue a statement of concern.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 5 March, the Azadi Sport Complex was bombed.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] An 8 March strike on Falak-ol-Aflak, which was marked with a blue shield emblem, damaged several sections of the site.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Strikes on Isfahan on 9 March damaged Naqsh-e Jahan Square, Chehel Sotoun, Ali Qapu, the Shah Mosque, Jameh Mosque, and Teymouri Hall.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 11 March, UNESCO urged protection for Iran's heritage sites and World Heritage Sites that have been damaged or are under high risk due to the war, alongside other historic sites in Israel, Lebanon, and the rest of West Asia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 17 March, blast waves and sharpnel damaged multiple palaces at Sa'dabad Complex in northern Tehran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Russia's Ministry of Foreign Affairs reported that strikes in Tehran on 1 April damaged the St.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Nicholas Orthodox Church and it's auxiliary buildings.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 7 April, the Rafi'-Nia synagogue was fully destroyed by the Israeli Air Force.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Israel declared a nationwide state of emergency, saying that the strikes on Iran were the largest that it had ever launched.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Israeli schools and workspaces were closed and public gatherings were canceled.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] In the 40 days from the start of the war through the 8 April ceasefire, there were a total of 650 missile attacks from Iran to Israel, the majority of which carried cluster munitions.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] About 16 of the missiles that made it past Israeli missile defenses carried conventional warheads, while 50 had cluster munitions.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The attacks killed a total of 24 people, all of them civilians, and resulted in more than 7,000 injuries.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Of the 24 civilians killed, 14 were struck by warheads with conventional explosive warheads and 10 were victims of cluster submunitions; two of the deaths were inside a sheltered space, with the other fatalities being people in unprotected areas.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The Israeli Coordinator of Government Activities in the Territories closed multiple aid crossings in the Gaza Strip, specifically interrupting free circulation on the Egypt–Gaza border.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Israeli forces suspended United Nations humanitarian movements and postponed planned rotations of international humanitarian staff, including medical evacuations and the return of people into Gaza, which the United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs condemned.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Israeli settler violence against Palestinians in occupied West Bank has increased; settlers have taken advantage of curbs on movement imposed during the renewed Israeli state of emergency.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The renewed blocking of West Bank roads in the context of the 2026 Lebanon war has delayed medics from assisting injured Palestinians.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The EU stated on 10 March that the Israeli actions were unacceptable and urged the Israeli authorities to make immediate efforts to prevent the violence against Palestinian civilians under international law, warning that "impunity for such acts risks provoking further violence".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Lebanon states more than one million people, 1/6th of the population, were displaced.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The Arab states of the Persian Gulf started a campaign of prosecution against civilians and foreign citizens that shared or reposted rumours from unverified sources about the Iranian attacks, with the stated main goal to curb misinformation that could harm public order.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Trump said "Even if we knew Gulf countries would be hit, big deal we did what we have to do".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Saudi Arabia invoked its Strategic Mutual Defence Agreement with Pakistan.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Pakistan deployed some 8,000 troops, a squadron of 16 aircraft, and two squadrons of drones.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] There was a pledge to send more if required.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 28 May, the US president Donald Trump threatened to 'blow up' Oman if it fails to "behave" in a casual aside during a cabinet meeting after reports of talks between Iran and Oman about jointly charging a toll for ships passing through the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Airstrikes on industrial and fuel hubs have released a chronic toxic cocktail of benzene, heavy metals, and persistent 'forever chemicals' (PFAS), triggering 'black rain' in major cities and causing long-term health degradation for civilians.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The war had global economic consequences: oil and gas prices surged, aviation and tourism were disrupted, and financial markets shuddered.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] International Energy Agency (IEA) head Fatih Birol described the situation as the "greatest global energy security challenge in history".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Oil and natural gas prices rose in direct response to Iranian threats to attack tankers and other ships and to Iranian strikes on oil facilities in Gulf producing countries.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] 20% of global oil and gas production normally transit the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] As the war continued, oil and gas prices ebbed and flowed as markets attempted to assess the likelihood of an end to the conflict.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Prices ranged from below $70 before the war to as high as $139 on 7 March.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Following the start of the war, multiple oil producers such as Shell, TotalEnergies, Britain's BP and others announced increased profits in their first quarter.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Toward the end of March significant shortages of domestic petroleum products emerged in southeast Asia as reserves ran out.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Stock markets initially fell, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average falling over 400 points (one percent) on 2 March alone, although by mid-April had recovered and reached record highs.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The UN World Food Programme and various economic analysts warned that the war is driving significant, long-term increases in global food prices.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Iran, which had access to the strait, had an increase in revenues.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Disruption in the supply of essential fertilizers due to the closure of the Strait threatened food production in many countries.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The Fertilizer Institute stated that nearly 50% of global urea and sulfur exports annually transited through the Strait of Hormuz, made worse by the natural gas shortage, which is a key feedstock for nitrogen fertilizers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Iran's airspace emptied of civilian aircraft during the conflict, as Bahrain, Iraq, Israel, Kuwait, Qatar, Syria and the UAE closed their respective airspaces.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Some carriers suspended service to the Middle East.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The disruption in global oil supply, caused by the closure of the Strait of Hormuz during the conflict, led to higher jet fuel prices, which increased operating costs for airlines and pushed up airfares on both domestic and international routes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Airlines responded by raising ticket prices and adjusting some flight schedules to cope with higher fuel costs.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] This impact was also visible in Europe, where continued disruptions in energy supply routes contributed to higher fuel prices and additional pressure on airlines.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] As a result, some carriers reduced capacity or cut flights, while others passed increased costs directly on to passengers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Spirit Airlines, an American low-cost airline, ceased operations on 2 May 2026, after increased fuel costs from the war exacerbated its existing financial difficulties.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Shipping traffic through the Strait of Hormuz, a major maritime choke point for world energy trade, has been largely blocked by Iran since 28 February 2026, when the United States and Israel launched an air war against Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] In retaliation, the Iranian Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) issued warnings forbidding passage through the strait, boarded and attacked merchant ships, and laid sea mines in the strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] From 13 April to 29 May 2026, the US simultaneously blockaded Iranian ports.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Until the war's start, about 25% of the world's seaborne oil trade and 20% of the world's liquefied natural gas (LNG) passed through the strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Soon after the start of the conflict, tanker traffic dropped to almost nothing.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 27 March, the IRGC announced that the strait was closed to any vessel going "to and from" the ports of the US, Israel, and their allies.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The International Maritime Organization reported on 21 April that about 20,000 mariners and 2,000 ships were stranded in the Persian Gulf due to the closure.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Amid fears of prolonged supply shortages, oil prices rose faster than during any other conflict in recent history; Brent crude oil prices surpassed US$100 per barrel on 8 March for the first time in four years, rising to US$126 per barrel at their peak.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The largest-ever monthly increase in oil prices occurred in March 2026.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The closure of the strait became the largest disruption to world energy supply since the 1970s energy crisis as well as the largest in the history of the world oil market.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Other commodity markets to suffer supply disruption and price increases due to the crisis include aluminum, fertilizer, and helium.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] In late March and early April, US president Donald Trump repeatedly threatened to destroy Iran's infrastructure if it did not reopen the strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 8 April a temporary ceasefire between Iran and the US was agreed and was to involve the reopening of the strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] However, following the failure of the Islamabad Talks, the US Navy itself began to blockade Iranian ports from 13 April.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The situation was described by *The Guardian* as a "dual blockade", with the US Navy blockading Iran and Iran blockading the Gulf.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 17 April, Iran announced that due to an Israel–Lebanon ceasefire agreement, it would allow commercial shipping, but the US continued its blockade of Iran, and Iran reimposed restrictions.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 4 May, Trump launched Operation Project Freedom, a US Navy mission to escort merchant ships out of the Gulf.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The Iranian military warned that this would be a ceasefire violation, and on 6 May, Trump paused Project Freedom because of "great progress" toward a possible agreement.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 17 June, Trump and Iranian president Masoud Pezeshkian signed a memorandum of understanding to end the war and the blockades of the strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 19 June, Trump announced a renewed ceasefire between Israel and Hezbollah, facilitated by the US, Qatar, and Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] However, Israel continued strikes in southern Lebanon, and the following day, Iran said that it closed the strait again, citing the Israeli actions as a violation of the agreement, a claim denied by the US military.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 27 June, the Joint Maritime Information Center (JMIC) overseen by the US Navy announced a widened route through the Strait of Hormuz near Oman, allowing increased naval traffic in both directions and indicating a challenge to Iran's control over the waterway.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Houthi-controlled Yemen threatened shipping in the Gulf of Aden and Red Sea.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Its threats had been suspended since 10 October 2025.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] March threats by Houthi leader Abdul-Malik al-Houthi had not stopped Red Sea traffic as of mid-April, although traffic remained under historic levels after crashing in 2024 as a result of Houthi attacks.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 15 March, the *Associated Press* reported that the weapons stockpile of the Houthis was running low from repeated attacks on Israel, while Iran had not been able to resupply them, because of the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Fundamental web infrastructure including S3 storage, EC2 compute and DynamoDB databases suffered complete outages in early March.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Iran shut down Internet access for its people throughout the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] According to a new report by the Center for International Policy, the US spent nearly $72 billion on the war ($1.2 billion per day on average).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The figure is nearly three times the amount of the Pentagon's official estimate.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] US military costs were estimated at $25–35 billion as of early April.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Israeli costs were estimated at $11 billion.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Costs to the Iranian economy were estimated at $40–50 billion, around 10% of GDP.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The monetary costs of Iranian attacks were much lower than the costs of neutralizing them: PATRIOT and THAAD interceptors are $4 million and $12 million, respectively, as opposed to $50,000 for a Shahed drone.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The war has also increased indirect military costs due to the rapid depletion of US munitions stockpiles.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] According to reports, the United States has used large quantities of high-cost interceptors such as Patriot and THAAD missiles, further increasing replacement expenses and strain on defense budgets.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The depletion of stockpiles has also affected US arms transfers and procurement decisions, including reports that Washington is reconsidering or delaying the transfer of Tomahawk cruise missiles to Germany and reviewing Germany's request for Typhon launchers due to limited availability.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Reports also indicate delays in missile deliveries to Japan and new procurement efforts, including an $842 million agreement for JASSM-ER cruise missiles from Denmark.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] US officials have raised concerns that existing stockpiles may be insufficient for sustained operations in multiple theaters, including in the event of a future conflict in Asia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The Pentagon has also expanded efforts to increase production capacity through programs aimed at scaling lower-cost "affordable mass" munitions and involving non-traditional defense contractors.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The US defence industry saw record stock surges during the war.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Before hostilities erupted, media attention on US-Iran tensions increased in early 2026, following failed nuclear talks and domestic unrest in Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Iranian state media, such as the IRNA, portrayed these developments as provocations.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Iranian state-controlled outlets have been described as employing propaganda techniques, including the use of AI-generated videos (such as those produced by Explosive Media) and inflated casualty figures.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Trump has accused Iran of using artificial intelligence as a "disinformation weapon." Iranian media broadcast manipulated images of alleged victories, prompting fact-checking from organizations like NewsGuard.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The video declares itself in remembrance of the Minab school attack and showcases Iran attacking various of its neighbours and American-Israeli outposts.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Before hostilities erupted, media attention on US-Iran tensions increased in early 2026, following failed nuclear talks and reports of Iranian domestic unrest.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Outlets such as CNN and *The New York Times* detailed US military buildups in the region, speculating about possible attacks.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Israeli broadcasters focused on the threats posed by Iranian proxies such as Hezbollah.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] In May 2026, *Israel Hayom* reported that Mossad had established a dedicated influence operations branch in 2021 under director David Barnea.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] According to the report, the unit conducted psychological and media campaigns targeting Iran through social media networks, online influencers, artificial intelligence–generated content, and the dissemination of information intended to undermine confidence in the Iranian government.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] A former senior Mossad official identified only as "O." stated that encouraging political change in Iran had become one of the agency's central objectives.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The report further alleged that the branch had participated in efforts to publicize compromising information about Iranian officials, influence public opinion during periods of unrest, and support broader Israeli strategies aimed at weakening the Islamic Republic's political stability.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Rumors that Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu had been killed in Iranian attacks were circulating widely on social media and were amplified by Iranian state-controlled outlets.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Netanyahu responded by posting several videos, including one filmed in a Jerusalem cafe in which he sarcastically declared that he was "dying for coffee" while holding up a cappuccino and holding up his hands to show that he had five fingers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The cafe video itself quickly became the subject of fresh rumors, with some social media users and commentators claiming that it too was AI-generated or a deepfake.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The cafe later released images as evidence that Netanyahu had visited.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Since the signing of the Islamabad Memorandum, the Israeli reactions to Trump and the declared end of hostilities towards Iran had been largely negative, with many expressing feelings of outrage and betrayal.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] For instance, *Israel Hayom* wrote in its headline "You could have been the greatest president of all, but you failed" and accused Trump of signing a surrender agreement and having humiliated his own country.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] As the airstrikes began, initial reporting relied heavily on satellite imagery and official briefings.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The Pentagon's announcements of the destruction of Iranian assets were widely echoed, but independent verification proved difficult due to Tehran's communications restrictions.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] *Slate* criticized American news coverage of the war, arguing that headlines too often treat statements from the Trump administration as objective and fail to also cover points of contradiction by Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The White House faced backlash over a video that mixed real war footage with video game clips.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Critics said such efforts distorted public understanding.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] PBS argued The Trump administration's use of video game footage, cartoon and blockbuster movie scenes for Iran messaging "risks reducing a real war to spectacle".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Trump has repeatedly shared provocative images regarding the Iran war such as a map of the US flag over Iran with words reading "United States of the Middle East?" and an AI-generated image of Iranian ships being bombed.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The White House circulates videos fusing real airstrike footages with visuals from video games and action movies, "transforming acts of destruction into a spectacle of national triumph", keeping the audience detached from the human suffering it produces.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Artists and entertainment companies often object to their works use in such clips.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Kesha's song "Blow" was used alongside footage of an airstrike and the caption "Lethality", which prompted the singer to post on X, "Stop using my music, perverts @WhiteHouse".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Blase Cupich, an American Catholic Cardinal who is close with Pope Leo XIV, referred to a video released by the White House of attacks on Iran mixed with Hollywood film clips as "horrifying" and "sickening".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 14 March 2026, Federal Communications Commission chairman Brendan Carr, a Trump appointee, warned broadcasters that those who "perpetrate fake news and distort the news" must "take the right course" or risk losing their licenses at renewal.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Carr said broadcasters "must act in the public interest, and if they don't, they will lose their licenses," citing the public's low trust in legacy media and past election coverage problems.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Trump expressed that he was "enthusiastic" about Carr's stance.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] In response to opposition of the war from Pope Leo XIV, Trump falsely claimed that the pope supported Iran having nuclear weapons and shared provocative memes on social media.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth also criticized the coverage during a news conference, taking issue with CNN's reporting and suggesting emphasizing Iranian frustration rather than adding to the headlines.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Democratic lawmakers condemned the FCC's remarks as unconstitutional censorship, with many calling it "oppressive" and a violation of the First Amendment.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 3 June 2026, the US House passed an act with a vote of 215-208 requiring the United States' war efforts to cease or gain approval from Congress to continue fighting.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On 23 June 2026, the US Senate enacted an act by a vote of 50-48 mandating the United States to either end its war operations or seek congressional consent to continue fighting.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] News media and traders have repeatedly applied the pejorative abbreviation "Trump Always Chickens Out" (TACO), previously used first for the Liberation Day tariffs, for Trump's repeated refusals to enforce his "red line" threats against Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Another pejorative abbreviation called "Not A Chance Hormuz Opens" (NACHO) was devised in reference to Trump's inability to quickly reopen the strait.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] *CNN* observed that over the course of the war, Trump's repeated talking points, such as his claim that Iran's military had been destroyed and another that Iranian leadership supposedly really wants to make a deal with Trump regarding the war, had been stated baselessly for months.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] *The Atlantic* argued that it was Trump who was visibly desperate for a deal and that Iran is able to exploit his needs.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] *Al-Monitor* reported that Netanyahu and his inner political circle view Trump's insistence on a deal as disastrous and blame him for failing to achieve regime change and victory against Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] New reports have determined suspicious insider trading patterns within the stock and oil markets in correlation with "positive" news of the war from Trump over several months.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Wall Street analysts and Iranian state media had accused journalist Barak Ravid of *Axios* of repeating false information from anonymous sources regarding ongoing negotiations to allow for market manipulation of oil prices.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] *The Wall Street Journal* argued that Trump directly intervened in the oil market by "jawboning" it, posting "positive" news of supposed negotiations to kill momentum of oil price increases by traders in quick responses to "negative" news.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] *CNN* observed that Trump incorrectly claimed that the US was close to an agreement with Iran to end the war more than 35 times from late March to early June, many of which involved Trump portraying Iran as supposedly "desperate".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Analysts accused Western media of failing to challenge the official narrative, with Mondoweiss highlighting the flattering language that downplayed civilian casualties.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Al Jazeera English noted the overrepresentation of voices from the pro-war Iranian diaspora.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Pre-war coverage was also marred by inadequate public warnings.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] On April 12, 2025, Iran and the United States began a series of negotiations aimed at reaching a nuclear peace agreement, following a letter from US president Donald Trump to Iranian supreme leader Ali Khamenei.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Trump set a 60-day deadline for Iran to reach an agreement.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] After the deadline passed without an agreement, Israel launched numerous strikes against Iran, igniting a war between the two countries in June.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The first round of high-level meetings was held in Oman on April 12, 2025, led by US special envoy Steve Witkoff and Iranian foreign minister Abbas Araghchi.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] At the time, both the White House and the Iranian Foreign Ministry said that the discussions held were constructive.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] A second round of Omani-mediated talks took place in Rome on April 19, 2025, again with indirect discussions between Witkoff and Araghchi.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] This was followed by a third round in Muscat around a week later, and an expert-level meeting to develop a framework for a possible nuclear agreement was led by Michael Anton for the US and by Majid Takht-Ravanchi for Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] After concluding that continued hostilities would risk economic calamity, Donald Trump signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU) on behalf of the United States during a ceremony at the Palace of Versailles on 17 June 2026.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The signing followed an earlier, digital signing of the MOU by the foreign ministers of the two principal belligerents.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] In the MOU, the United States and Iran agreed to suspend hostilities for 60 days and to establish a framework for a permanent peace under which the US would make major financial and political concessions to the Islamic Republic of Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Trump characterized the MOU as representing the "unconditional surrender" of Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Iran declared the document as an enduring "record of US failure".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The *Foreign Policy*, and *The Atlantic* described the outcome of the war as a "defeat" for the United States and Israel.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Moving forward, Iranian chief negotiator Mohammad Bagher Ghalibaf stated Iran would unilaterally begin imposing permanent tolls on ships passing the Strait of Hormuz 60 days following the withdrawal of the US Navy.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The war helped entrench the power of the IRGC within Iranian politics and society, and, according to Robert Pape, began the process of transforming Iran into a major power.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] US vice-president JD Vance announced on 22 June 2026 that in negotiations in Switzerland, Iran would again accede to the inspection of their nuclear facilities.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The content of the vice-president's statement were not confirmed by Iranian sources subsequently in a publication of June 23.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The 2026 Iran war has been analysed in terms of its possible military and political consequences for the Islamic Republic of Iran, and from international legal and geopolitical standpoints.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] A number of analysts have argued that, despite massive military and economic damage to Iran and the killing of large portions of the country's leadership, on a strategic level the war has been a success for Iran and a failure for the United States.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] In turn, Iran demonstrated that it could threaten US bases, undermining a widespread image of American military invulnerability.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Many experts argue that the war is illegal under US law because launching a war requires congressional authorization.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] They are also considered to be in violation of the UN Charter's prohibition on the use of force, because the attacks fail to meet the criteria for self-defense and lack authorization from the United Nations Security Council.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] In response, the Trump administration claimed that previous presidents have also launched unauthorized military actions, and dismissed international law.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] In international criminal law, experts have identified the attacks as a crime of aggression, specifically as a war of aggression.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] The US attack also violates the Algiers Accords (1981) in which the US agreed not to intervene politically or militarily in Iran's internal affairs.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/2026-iran-war-p04] Numerous critics and analysts identified the US-Israeli attack with a more open embrace of expansionism and imperialism by the Trump administration, and a departure from the norms of the liberal international order.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] Telephone numbers in Cyprus follow a closed telephone numbering plan which was adopted on 1 December 2001.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] As a result, for landline phone numbers the digit 2 followed by the old area code was affixed to the subscriber number and for mobile phones 9 was affixed to the phone number.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] The plan is also used in Akrotiri and Dhekelia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] Under the new system, these changed to numbers with eight digits, to be dialled from within Cyprus or abroad.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] As with fixed line numbers, under the new system, these changed to numbers with eight digits, to be dialled from within Cyprus or abroad.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] Numbering portability between the networks is possible.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] All numbers (except short codes) in Cyprus now have eight digits, hence the new numbering plan's promotional logo (in advertising) was an octopus called TESA (from Greek **Τελικό Εθνικό Σχέδιο Αριθμοδότησης** *Final National Numbering Plan*).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] Previously, landline numbers consisted of the trunk code 0, the area code, and a six-digit number.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] Mobile phone numbers had the prefix 09, followed by six digits, which had to be dialled in full.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] The 5 districts of Cyprus under government control each have their own 2 digit dialling code for landline numbers.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] (Note: Kyrenia District is fully within the area not under government control.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] After the district code, a 3 digit "area code" is written, which different for every town (Most towns have multiple codes, depending on how many numbers are in it).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] For example the prefixes 723 and 724 are used for Xylotymbou There isn't a list that displays all the codes, and from researching the yellow pages, the codes don't seem to be able to be narrowed down further and are mostly random.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] In Northern Cyprus, the Turkish numbering plan is used.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] The Turkish area code 0392 has been assigned for use with landline numbers, with 0533 Kuzey Kibris Turkcell and 0542 KKTC Telsim being used for mobile phones, while the Turkish country code +90 is used for calls from the rest of the world.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] For calls from the Republic of Cyprus to Northern Cyprus, the code 0139 followed by the 7-digit subscriber number is used, which are charged at local call rates.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] 0139 is still used for direct calls to Northern Cyprus even after the numbering plan change of December 2001.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] For calls from Northern Cyprus to the Republic of Cyprus, area code 0123 is used but the call is charged at international rates.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] It is also possible to use the international prefix 00357.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] These direct telephone connections between the two halves of the island are operated by the United Nations exchange, which allows direct telephone calls between the two communities is in place since 4 May 1998.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] After 2 March 2003, direct international calls from the Republic of Cyprus to Turkey are possible.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/357] Now callers from the Republic of Cyprus can call Northern Cyprus either through Turkey dialing 0090 392 xxxxxxx (calls charged at international rates), or using 0139 (calls charged at local rates).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] British Forces Cyprus are stationed on this territory, including Ayios Nikolaos Station for signals intelligence.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Despite being under British control, Akrotiri and Dhekelia are integrated with the surrounding Cypriot communities and economies.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The areas are notable for their strategic geopolitical value and rich environmental features, including the Akrotiri Salt Lake, a protected wetland.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Education, policing, and healthcare services are provided in coordination with the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The SBAs also play a significant role in intelligence and communications operations across the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Although not part of the European Union post-Brexit, the areas continue to be governed by protocols that align with certain EU laws to avoid disrupting the daily lives of residents.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Sovereign Base Areas were created in 1960 by the London and Zürich Agreements, when Cyprus achieved independence from the British Empire, as recorded by the United Nations in 1960 as treaty 5476.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The United Kingdom desired to retain sovereignty over these areas, as this guaranteed the use of UK military bases on Cyprus, including Royal Air Force (RAF) Akrotiri, and a garrison of the British Army.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The importance of the bases to the British is based on the strategic location of the island, at the eastern edge of the Mediterranean, close to the Suez Canal and the Middle East; the ability to use the RAF base as staging post for military aircraft; and for training.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In July and August 1961, there were a series of bomb attacks against the pipeline carrying fresh water to the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The pipeline was breached by explosions twelve times.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In the early 1970s, the United States built an over-the-horizon radar named Cobra Shoe, which could observe aeroplane operations and missile tests in southern Russia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] This was operated by the RAF on behalf of the U.S.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] This augmented an earlier British system built in the early 1960s named Project Sandra.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The American use of the base was hidden from the Cypriot government due to sensitivities between governments.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In 1974, following a military coup by the Cypriot National Guard, Turkey invaded the north of Cyprus, leading to the establishment of the internationally unrecognized Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] This did not affect the status of the bases.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Greek Cypriots fleeing from the Turkish forces were permitted to travel through the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area and were given humanitarian aid, with those from Achna setting up a new village (Dasaki Achnas or Achna Forest) which is still in the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Turkish advance halted when it reached the edge of the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area to avoid military conflict with the United Kingdom.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In the Akrotiri Sovereign Base Area a tented refugee camp was set up at "Happy Valley", part of the Episkopi Cantonment, to house Turkish Cypriots fleeing from Limassol and the villages surrounding the Area.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In 1975, they were flown out of RAF Akrotiri via Turkey to northern Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Some Greek Cypriot refugees remain housed on land in the parts of Trachoni and Kolossi villages that fall within the Akrotiri Sovereign Base Area.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] As a result of the Turkish invasion, the British Government reinforced its military presence in the Sovereign Base Areas on Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] While some reports suggest that prior to the invasion, the Government was looking to reduce Britain's presence on the island, following the invasion that proved to be strategically difficult.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Hence the British military presence remained on the island for the next fifty years.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] On 1 March 2026, as part of the 2026 Iran war, the base at Akrotiri was subject to a drone strike.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Ministry of Defence afterwards confirmed the drone was not launched from Iran.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] This preceded British Prime Minister Keir Starmer granting permission for U.S. forces to use the bases in the strikes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] No casualties were reported and only minor damage was sustained on the base's runway.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] On 2 March, two further drones were intercepted by RAF forces near the island.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] British authorities decided to evacuate both the Akrotiri and Dhekelia bases as a result of the attacks, prompting the Cypriot government to instruct an evacuation of Akrotiri village itself.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Government announced that British forces on the island would be reinforced, with additional fighter aircraft and Wildcat helicopters (equipped with anti-drone-capable Martlet missiles), in order to better protect British installations from attack.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Royal Navy would deploy the air defence destroyer HMS Dragon to the region.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Following multiple offensive airstrikes by Iran on Cyprus during the 2026 Iran War, the Hellenic Navy deployed advanced FDI HN frigate Kimon and a MEKO-class frigate, Psara, to the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The other area is Dhekelia Cantonment (Greek: Δεκέλεια pronounced [ðeˈceʎa]; Turkish: *Dikelya*), or the Eastern Sovereign Base Area (ESBA), which includes a base at Ayios Nikolaos plus parts of twelve village districts.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Joint Service Signal Unit (Cyprus) is located at Ayios Nikolaos Station, in the ESBA.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Ayios Nikolaus Station is an ELINT (electronic intelligence) listening installation of the UKUSA Agreement intelligence network.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The UKUSA signals intelligence system is sometimes known as "ECHELON".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The sovereign bases were retained in 1960 to keep military bases in areas under British sovereignty, along with the rights retained to use other sites in what became the territory of the Republic.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] That makes them different from the other British Overseas Territories.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Cypriot government issues licences for antiquity excavation in the SBAs subject to British consent, and any movable antiquities found in excavations or otherwise discovered become Cypriot state property.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The territory is administered by an Administrator, who is also the Commander of British Forces Cyprus, which as of March 2026 is Major General Tom Bewick.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Administrator is officially appointed by the British monarch on the advice of the Ministry of Defence.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Administrator has all the executive and legislative authority of a governor of an overseas territory.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] A Chief Officer is appointed, and is responsible to the Administrator for the day-to-day running of the civil government, with subordinate Area Officers responsible for the civil administration of the two areas.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] British citizens are normally entitled to vote in United Kingdom elections, as British Forces or overseas electors.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The areas have their own legal system, distinct from the United Kingdom and the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] This consists of the laws of the Colony of Cyprus as of August 1960, amended as necessary.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The laws of Akrotiri and Dhekelia are closely aligned with, and in some cases identical to, the laws operating within the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Court of the Sovereign Base Areas is concerned with non-military offences committed by any person within Akrotiri and Dhekelia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Law and order is maintained by the Sovereign Base Areas Police.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Offences involving British Forces Cyprus and military law are dealt with by the Cyprus Joint Police Unit.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Fire and rescue services are provided by the Defence Fire and Risk Management Organisation through stations at Episkopi, Akrotiri, Dhekelia and Ayios Nikolayos.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Defence Medical Services provide emergency ambulance cover based from medical centres in the main bases.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] All emergency services are accessible from any telephone using the Europe-wide emergency number 112.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Labour government, under whom the proposal appeared, was replaced by the Cameron–Clegg coalition whose defence review did not mention the issue.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Republic of Cyprus claims that the Sovereign Base Areas are a "remnant of colonialism".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] On 30 June 2005 the House of Representatives of Cyprus unanimously adopted a resolution on the legal status of the base areas originally proposed by Vassos Lyssarides.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The UK government does not recognise Cypriot claims that the UK's sovereignty in the areas is limited.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In July 2001, protests were held at the bases by local Cypriots, unhappy with British plans to construct radio masts at the bases as part of an upgrade of British military communication posts around the world.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Locals claimed the masts would endanger local lives and cause cancer, as well as have a negative effect on wildlife in the area.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Sovereign Base Areas Administration has carried out assessments and surveys into the effects on wildlife, which have fed into an "Akrotiri Peninsula Environmental Management Plan", published in September 2012.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In 2004, the UK offered to cede 117 square kilometres (45 sq mi) of farmland as part of the rejected Annan Plan for Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In some Cypriot media it was stated that the proposed interdiction of the Syrian civil war, utilising Akrotiri and Dhekelia, could recklessly endanger the Cypriot populations near to those bases.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Two days earlier, on 27 August 2013, Cypriot foreign minister Ioannis Kasoulides had moved to calm Cypriot concerns, saying that the British bases were unlikely to play a major part in any intervention.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] A spike in the US Air Force arms delivery from US and NATO depots in Europe to Akrotiri was reported by the Israeli newspaper Haaretz, and "the illegal presence of thousands of American soldiers" at the base have drawn criticism.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] During his 2024 visit to the base dispatching surveillance planes to Gaza, the British prime minister Keir Starmer noted, "We can't necessarily tell the world what you're doing here" "for reasons that are obvious to you, the whole world is relying on you".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Surveillance planes continued being dispatched towards Gaza after the ceasefire between Israel and Hamas began.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In March 2026, during the 2026 Iran war, a drone strike was launched against the bases by Hezbollah.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Following the attack, the diplomatic tension raised higher between Britain and Cyprus, as domestic protests criticized the presence of the bases and being dragged into regional conflict.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In April 2026, British Minister for the Armed Forces Al Carns, made it clear that there will be no negotiation about the bases, or ceding sovereignty over the bases.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] There is normally no passport check at the border from Akrotiri or Dhekelia to Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Perhaps to help reduce any tensions in the area, outside of the bases much of the territory is indistinguishable from that controlled by Cyprus and casual visitors may not realize that they have crossed an international border.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The main road connecting all major cities on Cyprus's southern shore run non-stop through SBA: Some 7 km (5 miles) of the A6 highway through Akrotiri SBA and some 16 km (10 miles) of the A3 highway through Dhekelia SBA.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] More formal controls do exist at the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus boundary.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Possession of a passport or an EU-compliant national identity card is generally needed in Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] A passport is required to travel between Cyprus/SBAs and Northern Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Issues concerning the validity of car insurance and customs are specified by SBAs' administration.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Under Article 2(1) of the Protocol, the SBAs were partially part of the European Union Customs Union in three domains: VAT, agriculture and fisheries.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] However, the SBAs were already outside the EU.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Therefore, concerns were raised about the future status of about 15,000 Cypriots (EU citizens) working in the SBA following the UK's 2020 departure from the EU.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Cyprus, Ireland and Spain were the only three EU states that conducted bilateral talks with the UK on the Brexit issue.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The talks between the UK and the Republic of Cyprus started in October 2017.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Brexit withdrawal agreement has a protocol on the SBAs, with provisions essentially maintaining their previous status.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Akrotiri and Dhekelia cover 3% of the land area of Cyprus, a total of 254 km2 (98 sq mi) (split 123 km2 (47 sq mi) (48.5%) at Akrotiri and 131 km2 (51 sq mi) (51.5%) at Dhekelia).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Akrotiri and Dhekelia have a border of 48 km (30 mi) and 108 km (67 mi) with Cyprus respectively.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Akrotiri also has a longer coastline than Dhekelia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] 60% of the land is privately owned as freeholds by Cypriot citizens; the other 40% is controlled by the Ministry of Defence as Crown leasehold land.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In January 2014, an agreement between the Cypriot and UK governments was signed, ensuring that residents and property owners in the British Bases will enjoy equal rights for the development of property.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In addition to Akrotiri and Dhekelia, the Treaty of Establishment also provided for the continued use by the British Ministry of Defence and the British Armed Forces of certain facilities within the Republic of Cyprus, known as *Retained Sites*.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Akrotiri is located in the south of the island, near the city of Limassol (or Lemesos).
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Dhekelia is in the southeast, near Larnaca.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Both areas include military bases, as well as farmland and some residential land.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Akrotiri is surrounded by territory controlled by the Republic of Cyprus, but Dhekelia also borders on the United Nations (UN) buffer zone and the area controlled by the Turkish forces.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The villages of Xylotympou and Ormideia, also in the Republic of Cyprus, are enclaves surrounded by Dhekelia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Dhekelia Power Station, divided by a British road into two parts, also belongs to the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The northern part is an enclave, like the two villages, whereas the southern part is located by the sea, and therefore not an enclave, though it has no territorial waters of its own.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Territorial waters of 3 nautical miles (5.6 km) are claimed, and the right according to the laws of the UN to extend the claim of up to 12 nautical miles (22.2 km) is reserved.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Cyprus is an important migration flyway for birds between Africa and Europe and millions of birds are killed yearly as they migrate over the island.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] To protect resident and migratory birds, BirdLife Cyprus and the RSPB survey areas of illegal trapping.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] More than 150 species of birds, over half of conservation concern, have been trapped in nets, or on limesticks, and it is estimated that organised crime gangs earn over 15 million euros yearly.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The dead birds are sold to provide the main ingredient for ambelopoulia — an illegal delicacy — in the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The 2015 survey estimated a maximum 19 km (12 mi) of mist nets across both the Republic and the British Territories, and more than 5,300 limesticks removed, mainly in the Republic.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] It is estimated that over 2 million birds were killed in 2015 including over 800,000 on British Territories.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Employing measures such as covert camera surveillance, including a drone, exclusion zones and impounding vehicles, trapping activity at Dhekelia fell by 77.5%.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In 2016, an estimated 800,000 birds were killed at Dhekelia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In 2017, trapping activity fell by 77.5% and bird deaths to an estimated 180,000.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Episkopi Cliffs Important Bird Area lies mostly within the western base area, and covers much of the peninsula.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] It was identified as an IBA in 1989, and became recognised under the Ramsar Convention in 2003.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] 60% was designated as a Special Protection Area in 2010.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Over 300 bird species have been recorded in this area.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The wetlands, including the large salt lake, are an important habitat and bird hotspot.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] These wetlands are an important breeding spot for the ferruginous duck, which has nested there since 2005.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Other species that nest in the wetlands include the black-winged stilt, the Kentish plover, the spur-winged lapwing, and the stone-curlew.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Black francolins, Cyprus wheatears, Cyprus warblers, Eleonora's falcons, peregrine falcons, griffon vultures, European shags, European rollers, blue rock thrushs, and wallcreepers breed elsewhere in the area, especially around the cliffs.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The beaches in the British Sovereign Base Areas (SBAs) are important nesting sites for the endangered green *Chelonia mydas* and loggerhead *Caretta caretta* turtles.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The SBA Environment Department, assisted by a large volunteer effort, has monitored turtle nesting success on SBA beaches since 1990.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Disturbance to nesting turtles is an issue in some areas due to activities such as camping, driving on beaches and illegal fishing.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Sea turtles in Cyprus are protected as priority species under the Protection and Management of Nature and Wildlife Ordinance (implementing the provisions of the Habitats Directive), enacted in 2007.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In December 2015, five Special Areas of Conservation (SACs) were designated in the Cyprus Sovereign Base Areas.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The five SACs designated are Akrotiri, Episkopi, Cape Pyla, Dhekelia and Agios Nikolaos.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The designations were made under the Protection and Management of Nature and Wildlife Ordinance and will support the existing network (NATURA 2000) of SACs in Cyprus and across Europe.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] When the areas were being established, the boundaries were deliberately drawn to avoid centres of population.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Approximately 18,195 people live in the areas.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] About 11,000 native Cypriots work in the areas, or on farmland within the boundaries of the areas.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The British military and their families make up the rest of the population.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Persons related to the territory may in theory be eligible to claim the British Overseas Territories citizenship (BOTC status) through a personal connection to the areas, i.e., birth on the territory before 1983, or born after 1983 to a parent who was born on the territory before 1983.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In comparison, the 2002 Act bestowed British citizenship on all other BOTCs.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Hence, non-British and non-military personnel with a connection to the territory cannot live and work in the UK, and must use their Cypriot passports to apply for visas to the UK.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Under the terms of the 1960 agreement with Cyprus establishing the Sovereign Base Areas, the United Kingdom is committed not to use the areas for civilian purposes.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] This was stated in 2002 as the primary reason for the exclusion of the areas from the scope of the British Overseas Territories Act 2002.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] As of 2010, around 7,195 service personnel of British Forces Cyprus are based at Akrotiri and Dhekelia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Service Children's Education oversees education for children of personnel and MoD employees.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Eastern Sovereign Base Area is served by Dhekelia Primary School and Ayios Nikolaos Primary School, which are feeders for King Richard School.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Western Sovereign Base Area is served by Episkopi Primary School and Akrotiri Primary School, which are feeders for St.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] No economic statistics are gathered for Akrotiri and Dhekelia.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The main economic activities are the provision of services to the military, as well as limited agriculture.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] When the territory under the effective control of the Republic of Cyprus switched currencies from the Cypriot pound to the euro in January 2008, Akrotiri and Dhekelia followed suit, making the Sovereign Base Areas the only territory under British sovereignty to officially use the euro.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Cypriot motorways pass through both areas, the most prominent case being the A3 motorway which runs for approximately 16km (10 miles) within the Dhekelia area.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] There is no public airport within the areas, but the RAF Akrotiri airbase is located there, which has a runway suitable for long-distance flights, but is not used for public flights.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The closest civilian international airport to the Akrotiri area is Paphos International Airport 40km (25 miles) away, while the closest to the Dhekelia area is Larnaka International Airport 15km (10 miles) away.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] As with the rest of Cyprus, there is no rail transport within the two areas.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Base Areas form part of the Republic of Cyprus telephone numbering plan, using the international prefix +357.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Landline numbers are in the same eight-digit format, with the last four digits being the line number.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Numbers in Dhekelia begin with the digits 2474.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Those in Akrotiri begin with the digits 2527.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The bases are issued different amateur radio call signs from the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Amateur radio stations on the bases use the International Telecommunication Union prefix of "ZC4", which is assigned to Great Britain.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] There are about 52 amateurs licensed in this manner.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Amateur radio direction finding identified RAF Akrotiri as the location of the powerful but now defunct shortwave numbers station "Lincolnshire Poacher".
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Several curtain antennas there have been identified as being used for these transmissions.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] BFBS Radio 1 and 2 are broadcast on FM and can be widely received across Cyprus.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] BFBS Television is now only available to viewers via satellite, having been confined to the SBAs or encrypted in 1997 for copyright reasons, before BFBS switched off its analogue transmitters in 2009.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The British East Mediterranean Relay Station was situated locally.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The most successful association football team in the territory is Ethnikos Achna FC in the Dhekelia region.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] They play in the Cypriot football league system and have played in the top tier Cypriot First Division for most of their existence.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] They represented Cyprus in the 2006–07 UEFA Cup, losing to RC Lens from France in Round 1.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Their stadium, Dasaki Stadium, hosted 6 matches in the 2024 UEFA European Under-17 Championship.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Other teams in the territory also play in the Cypriot league system, for instance APEA Akrotiri.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] A separate league for British military teams, the Cyprus Forces Football League, is run by the Royal Air Force FA.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Commander British Forces Cyprus Sporting Competition (CBF Cup), a multi-sport competition between teams representing bases and resident British infantry battalions, is held annually.
[src:akrotiri-and-dhekelia/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The territory does not send delegations to the Commonwealth Games, and have not sent athletes to the Olympic Games through the British Olympic Association.
